The light has a friction adjustment, that is the mating of two surfaces with ridges.
There ARE NO GEARS.
You unloosen the wing nut a bit and adjust the light angle up or down and tighten the wing nut.
There is no sideways adjustment so watch how you position it when you install.
One nice feature is, it comes with the pictured ground stake AND a flat pedestal (not shown in picture) for attaching the light to a flat surface.
Either is mounted to the light with the above mentioned bolt and wing-nut.
You also get two long screws and plastic screw inserts that you tap into a drilled hole (for the mounting screws if you use them) I didnt.
The light had a nice weather seal around my little 50 Watt outdoor flood light bulb.
My location uses the flat pedestal under a shelf so Im not too concerned about water.
There is NO on-off switch, when its plugged in is ready to power the light (remember it has NO switch).
Amazon has some nice illuminated plugin switches if you need on but I didnt.
So, at this point in time it turns on and off fine.
We are headed into Fall and Winter here in Indiana USA so that will be the real stress test but this is also the rainy season.
You use this with a GFI (ground Fault Interrupter) which shuts off the power if something (like water) shorts to ground.
Everything I have outside is on a GFI.
It uses the standard normal 120 Volt screw in light socket (for USA anyway) but I would only use a bulb that is rated for outdoors.
Rain splashing  on a hot indoor bulb gives me the willies....
The cord looked about 5 or 6 foot in length (I didnt measure) Its all GREEN but I dont care.
IF, I experience any problems with this I will update and change the stars from 5 to whatever.
Just remember this is NOT a Low Voltage Light.
So take normal precautions as it could hurt you.
(120 Volts AC) Dont let water get into the power plug, if you do the GFI should remove the power.
Dont use this outdoors without using a GFI socket.
Info: GFI sockets are used around sinks and bathrooms where there is water near electricity.
At this point Im happy with this and will save the push in ground stake in case I relocate.
I hope this helps you with your decision and I will update if needed.
BTW have a happy Fall and Winter!
My first one would not turn off at all when the timer should have stopped it.

Well see if the replacement package has also problems or not.

ThisWestinghouse Lighting 3796300 3-Way Daylight Compact Fluorescent Twist Light Bulbis the real thing, a true daylight 6500 Kelvin daylight 3-way bulb with an industry standard E26 medium screw-in base.

Rated as a 12/19/28-Watt 3-way CFL bulb, it it the equivalent of a conventional 30/70/100-Watt 3-way incandescent light bulb, and it should fit any standard lamp that accepts 3-way bulbs, especially those of the open torchiere style.
Just be sure that the base is the E26 medium screw-in standard.
The big difference between this bulb and others is that its rated at 6500 K (Kelvin), which is its color temperature.

Kelvin Color Temperatures:Trying to not get too technical, color temperature is a description of the warmth or coolness of a light source, and describes the characteristics of visible light that have important applications in lighting, photography, videography, and other fields.

Color temperature is usually stated in the unit of absolute temperature, the Kelvin, having the unit symbol K. Higher Kelvin temperatures (3600-6500 K) are considered cool, and lower color temperatures (2700-3000 K) are considered warm.

Cool light is generally preferred for visual tasks because it produces higher contrast than warm light, while warm light is preferred for living spaces because it is more flattering to skin tones and clothing.
Bulbs with a color temperature of 2700-3600 K are generally found in most indoor general lighting applications.
This Westinghouse 3-Way Daylight CFL bulb with its 6500 K rating is the equivalent of overcast daylight, and for some, its the perfect light for work spaces.
It does not have that greenish cast that we associate with conventional fluorescent tubes found in most office spaces.

In comparison, the electronic flash used with most cameras is usually rated at 5,500-6,000 K, while Cool White/Daylight CFL bulbs are often rated at 5,000 K. Standard incandescent lamps have ratings around 2,500 to 3,300 K. If you prefer a warmer 3-way bulb, theGE 47448 12/23/29-Watt CFL Energy Smart Spiral 3-Way Light Bulbis rated at 2,700 K, which puts it in the Warm White range.
Others such as theSylvania 29913 CFL replacement for 3-way lampsare rated at 3000 K. The choice is yours.
Ive found thisWestinghouse Lighting 3796300 3-Way Daylight CFL Twist Bulbto be an excellent light source as a work light, especially while on the computer or working with photos.
Its light is clean and not distracting, and the fact that its rated life is 10,000 hours is a plus.8/16/2012

I am a hobbyist, and am used to the power that Lippo batteries can deliver compared to their same wattage counterparts, in most cases you need speed controllers and different motors to handle them without burning something up.
This is where the next generation of tools comes from, if you look at the amps these batteries can put out you can see where the power comes from.
I am not sure about these ( as I could not find that much info on them) but I am sure these are really 11.2 volt batteries, which would be 3 cell lippos, with at least an max output of 30-40 amps.
Compared to conventional NI-CAD batteries pale in comparison.

Lippo batteries hold twice the charge and do not dwindle over age (in other words deliver full power until they die, which this tool must have something built in to prevent that as once a lippo is completely depleted can kill the battery) and do not have any memory effect.
The reason I say these are really 11.2 volt lippos is that is how they come as each lippo cell is 3.7 volts, unlike conventional 1.2 volts.
Also when they are charged they normally charge to well above their rating, these probably charge to 12.6 volts.

Ive always used and hated those cheap crimpers that come with the sets at the home centers... they are hard on the hands, and either destroy the connector insulation or dont fully crimp, or both.
This crimper solves both problems.
Its easy on the hands, the ratchet makes sure you get a full crimp, and on top of that, the jaws do a better job of crimping fully without destroying insulation.

The ratchet mechanism also lets you put the connector in the jaws, close to the first click, and the jaws will hold the connector while you worry about inserting the wire to the proper location... no more "put connector on the wire, reach for the crimper, pick up the connector and put it back on the wire, hope it stays there while you start crimping" stuff.
The jaw sets for different purposes are also good, and change easily in seconds, without tools... just pull them out, and plug in the next set.
Ive used crimpers costing 5 times as much for doing DB-25 pins that dont work much better than these, and the expensive ones only did the one job.
If you need to crimp connectors, these work well and the price is nice!

The Brondell Swash 1000 is a well engineered and well built product that just works.
It does what it is supposed to do, and does it quietly.
My wife had bugged me about getting a bidet ever since we stayed in a B and B that had one earlier this summer.
Up until then, we were bidet-ignorant like most Americans.

After spending a lot of review time on the internet (who knew there were so many brands out there), i went with the Swash 1000 based on other reviews, and these factors that seemed important to me: 1) It has a sturdy lid that can be sat upon.
2) It provides endless warm water.
3) Stainless steel nozzles 4) Adjustable nozzle location.
The installation is a snap, only about 30 minutes.
My main problem was putting in an outlet to plug the thing into.. not many houses are built with the idea of needing to plug any thing in next to a toilet.
Once connected, the thing just works ... no issues at all.
The instructions are simple to follow, and well illustrated.
One negative: The supply hose is fugly.
Brondell should include some fittings to turn this hose down so it wont be unsightly.
As shipped, it makes a horizontal loop from the underside of the toilet tank to the inlet connection on the Swash ... like I said, it is fugly.
Brondell has fitting available to remedy this (for $ 9 each, plus shipping) .... seems like they would throw those in with a $ 600.00 seat .... but they dont.
Packaging is very good for the seat, it arrived very quickly (2 days) and in perfect condition.
Operation is flawless so far.
Actually, I thought only my wife would use the thing, but after trying it out I really like it myself ... now I dont like having to download anywhere except at home.
Id recommend the Swash to anyone contemplating buying a bidet seat.
Its a good thing ....

I am very pleased with this Tulip Table Lamp by Normande Lighting.

However it should work equally well with candelabra base LED bulbs.
The included bulbs are full-spectrum bulbs which produce a light that is often descibed as bluish but with the brown/tan colored shades the light did appear to have a green tint.
This type of bulb is excellent for reading but not always pleasing to the eye.

I am still very pleased with the lamp but have updated the bulbs yet again to a couple of candelabra base LED bulbs which I purchased locally.
These 2-watt LED bulbs are instant on like incandescent bulbs but have substantial energy savings over both CFL and incandescent bulbs putting out the incandescent equivalent of 30-watts each.
Admittedly the light is more attractive than that of the CFL type I had been using.

This is a rather small unit and easy to find a home for.
For the most part, the device has worked well for the month Ive had it.
I think the supplied power pack used to move the controller around the home to include Z-Wave devices feels a little awkward but I really dont know how I would have designed the unit.
Because of this, Ive mounted the controller in an accessible area of my comms closet so I can move it to the devices location once I add light switches and power plugs.
The local Web interface is HTTP only, and there is no password protection / user account management, although the device supports an SSL connection to mios.
com (I think thats the right URL) and user authentication for remote access.
Anyway, the device appears to always make an outbound connection to their servers even if I dont want to use my Droid X to control the locks.

I currently do use my Droid X so Ive permitted the outbound connection, and I appreciate the SSL connection using Home Buddy (Android app), but I have an SSL VPN solution that permits secured inbound connections and I am migrating away from their service... but I cannot determine how to turn off their service other than maybe removing DNS entries or blocking at my firewall or something.
This isnt much of an issue for most people because they may not employ OpenVPN, or some other SSL/TLS VPN solution, but I do and would like to be able to disable the call home feature.
I believe the call home may also used for firmware update notifications.
I have crashed the controller several times and had to power off / power on to regain control.
Most of these events were during initial setup and when I was accessing the Web server from my Android tablet.
Not really sure what the issue was but now that the devices are added, and my scenes and events are configured, the controller works for what I need.
I do need to incorporate this with my alarm panel but havent gotten there yet.

When setting up devices and/or events, some of the configurable options are a little cryptic so Im not sure if my current issue with my Kwikset locks could be corrected through a configuration parameter that I cannot figure out.
Some of the options appear to be labeled as they are in the internal database, which is easy and may mean something to the developers but doesnt mean anything to me.

To be fair, I havent done much more than lurk on the support forums for the Vera 2 and although some of the labels might be cryptic, Ive been able to add my devices, name them, and place them into different rooms.

I use this for edge rounding and cutting out handles in hardwood.

It is well made, I find the light very usefull and the clear plastic base is great to actually see the work.
It has 6 speeds, but cutting into Australian hardwood (DENSE!)
I tend to always need either speed 5 or 6.
This doesnt cause any problems, but the slower speeds would only be useful for softwoods.
It has an optional fence attachment which I feel is a must for this router.
Its very easy to fit and makes routing straight lines a breeze.
To raise or lower the bit requires unclamping the front latch (black latch in the picture) and winding the Dewalt collar (also pictured) of the router to raise or lower the shaft.
This works well, but has an ever so slight amount of slop in it.

I find after I reclamp the latch, I can wind the collar just a fraction more (Which I do to keep it tight) Not a huge issue how I use it, but it means there is probably a 1/16 to 1/32" of movement after you have set it.
Just means you need to measure the bit height AFTER you have set it.
All up for the price, I think this is great value for money.

We purchased a new house about 2  years ago and its a nice house but they faucets werent anything special.
They are pretty standard and dont look so pretty anymore.
So I replaced my standard faucet with this one.
As soon as I took it out of the box I could tell it was a very high quality faucet.
It is costly but based on the quality I would expect it to last decades instead of years like many faucets.
It was fairly easy to install and only took about 45 minutes and that included time to thoroughly clean the sink prior to mounting the new faucet.
The instructions were clear and easy to understand but you will need a helper to hold the faucet in place while you tighten it.
Otherwise it tends to move out of place as you tighten the screw.
You get to choose whether you want the handle to the left or right when you mount it.
If you are replacing a faucet that has a separate sprayer then you will need to purchase a plug to fill the sink hole.
The plug isnt included with this faucet.
The faucet operates differently than any other faucet that I have ever owned but I have learned to really like it.
You push the handle down to turn the water on, up to turn it off.
You pull it forward for hot water and back for cold water if you mount the handle to the left side.
I think it will be reversed if you mount the handle to the right side.
This faucet is entirely stainless steel.
It doesnt have any clear handles to get dirty looking like many other faucets.
The faucet has a very high arc with a pull-down sprayer that is built right in.
The sprayer offers very smooth movement with a reflex system that will automatically pull it back in when not in use.
The sprayer will allow you to switch between aerated stream and powerful spray and will also allow you to pause or temporarily shut off the water flow from the sprayer.
This is a fantastic faucet and I think it is well worth the investment.
All of our appliances are stainless steel and this faucet looks great with them.

I bought this dimmer to use with a floor lamp in our bedroom.

Ive been a very satisfied LightWedge customer for years.
Yes, at times the pages stick to the LightWedges surface, but that doesnt prevent me from being able to read my book.
Truth be known, its easier for me to read when the pages DO stick to the surface!
In addition, using my LightWedge has become the topic of conversation at bars and restaurants I frequent:  What IS that?

Where can I get one?I looked to the rechargeable LED version as an upgrade (never mind looking to save money on buying batteries) for not only myself but also my boss who, I recently learned, has a Kindle (how great to use the same USB to outlet connection to charge the LightWedge) but has yet to read an entire Kindle book because she, just like I, likes the entire holding a book thing.
I ordered two factory sealed rechargeable units from Amazon and both arrived on time; however, one didnt include the cable.

While my return was handled promptly, Im glad I decided to have both shipped directly to me as I cant imagine what would have happend had my boss received a birthday present LightWedge box that was missing the cable.
Id also like to point out that while the Rechargeable LightWedge comes with, I forget the exact term used, a protector or case, in my opinion its more like one of those Crown Royal bags.
Also, as others have reviewed, they fit snug.
Id prefer to better protect my LightWedge gift and bought a LightWedge Original (its larger than the paper back book version) Soft Case for less than $10.
Ill update my review of the Rechargeable LightWedge when the replacement arrives in the next couple of days.

May 30 Update:  Posted a question about the dimensions of this Rechargeable Unit and received a prompt response that its the same as the Original hard cover book version I ordered way back when vs the paper back version.
Another replied that it was a great product.
July 28 Update:  Used this LED LightWedge for the first time on Fri and really like the option of 2 light intensities.
On for a little over an hour on Fri, I was all set to use the unit again this evening (Sun), but it already needed a recharge.
TBH, I wasnt expecting this LED LightWedge to be so attached to an outlet and wonder if sticking with the battery version would have been a wiser move.
Sept 1 Update:  Down to One Star as I charged the unit this morning since I was planning on using it this evening and the light lasted 2 hours.
(Another reviewer mentioned that the charge held for 15 hours.
Based upon my personal experience, Im of the opinion that those 15 hours include the hours spent in the off position.
)This LightWedge should be marketed to people who read at night near an outlet--for example, those reading at home or in a hotel/motel room--since they can charge and read and then quickly recharge.
If, like me, you need a light when dining out, the charge life isnt acceptable; plus when the charge dies, your book is in the dark unless you carry the charger with you AND can find an outlet handy.
With the battery operated version, it is easy enough to carry extra batteries.
Dont get me wrong, I really love the LightWedge; but until the charge lasts in the off position like my Kindle and Garmin, Im better off with a battery LightWedge.
Since I gave away my original battery powered LightWedge, I just ordered another.
Cant wait to unload this rechargeable LED unit and if someone wants to just pay me for postage, you can have it for free!

This is my second Skilsaw, my first being a worm-drive behemoth bought in 1975 that still runs like new but is too heavy for me to use now that I am no longer a framer with massive forearms.
My first project using the new, more modest saw was a storage shed.
I have these initial thoughts to offer:It has plenty of power.
It is not heavy but it is a two-handed saw.
Cross cutting full depth into 4x4 cedar  admittedly a soft wood - did not slow the saw at all.
The supplied 24-tooth blade is of excellent quality and is very sharp.
The saw cuts straight and clean.
The depth markings are easy to read and use.
The blade is on the right side of the saw (different from my worm-drive).
I found it a bit difficult to see where the blade first enters the wood.
This makes the notched guide and the laser guide critical.
And here my particular unit has a problem: It cuts 3/64 to the right of the 90-degree notch and the laser line.
It should cut on the notch and laser line.
To compensate, I either have to mark cuts 3/64 shorter than the length I want, or keep the notch and laser line that much to the left of my measured and marked line.
If anyone knows a way to adjust the saw or otherwise compensate for this, I would appreciate learning how.
All other settings and alignments were true and square.
I found the safety button near the trigger an unnecessary complication  - an extra control to fiddle with when I should be concentrating on the cuts accuracy.
The saw did not come with a rip fence.
It did come with a rugged carrying bag big enough for the saw, extra blades and a rip fence (I purchased one).
The power indicator light was a useful safety feature; reminding me the unit was plugged in.
I would give this tough saw five stars save for the blade on my unit being 3/64 out of line with the notch and laser guides.
A tough job made easy is why a power tool like this makes the price paid for it worthwhile.
This tool is powerful enough to get the work done without worry and time lost trying to make a less powerful drill do the job.
I am very happy to have it in my workshop.
It arrived ahead of the delivery date which was a bonus to the quality tool.

Our situation:  We live in a double-wide mobile home with eight foot ceilings everywhere except the great room/living room--its cathedral ceiling is a couple feet taller.
From the day we moved in weve hated that room and wondered how much it would cost to convert it to a lower ceiling.
NO NEED, PROBLEM SOLVED WITH THIS FAN!!

The worst thing about a situation like ours (mobile home with silly cathedral ceilings) is not just the heat in the great room, but how all the other rooms have to be freezing in the summer just to make it breathable in the great room.

(Plus the thermostat is located in the great room)We tried everything over the years--sitting box fans in the cold parts of the house and trying to suck/blow the cool air over into the hot room--running the ceiling fan in the hot room constantly and not letting the hot air build up--or doing the opposite, not running the ceiling fan and just letting it build up and stay there.
We tried various things, nothing with much success.

"Last year we installed two additional register vents in the ""great hot room"" hoping that would not only add cool air to the room via the air conditioner, but maybe because of the additional registers blowing in the hot room, the registers in the cold rooms wouldnt blow quite so hard."
It helped, but I still had to close off one of the registers in a bedroom as it continued to freeze the people in that room during air conditioning months.
The extra vents helped, but the great room continued to be noticeably warmer than the rest of the house.
And this year I started thinking about a through the wall fan.

After reading the reviews here on Amazon, and seeing most people were using the fan to get the heat from rooms with a wood burning stove to disperse to other parts of their house--I thought, Ive got a wood burning stove in my ceiling, yessiree.

"And I want that heat out of there--and the room right next door is always freezing--so lets suck it out of the hot room and into the cold room!I decided if I could ""tell even a little bit of difference"" Id buy a second fan."
We cut the hole in the wall, for the fan, a few inches down from the ceiling on the cold rooms side, therefore it is about 20 inches or so down the wall on the side with the cathedral ceiling.
Weve had it for over a couple of weeks now, and Im still feeling giddy.
I walk back and forth between the two sides, grinning like an idiot.
Youd think I invented something that was going to make me rich the way I brag about it to everyone!
There is absolutely NO REASON to buy a second fan.
For the first time in ten years, the houses temperature is balanced throughout!

Like many woodworkers, I use this as a second blade on my Kapex.
It is less than 1/2 of the price of the Festool 60tooth blade that comes with the Kapex, so I keep my Festool blade in reserve for the cleanest, most precise cutting needs.
I have used Oshlun FesPro blades as Festool blade substitutes for many years and have never been disappointed.
I have several Oshlun blades for my for my Festool TS55 track saw that I originally got for cutting sheetstock and recycled lumber.
I also have used Oshlun blades on my table and chop saws.
Ive found Oshlun blades to be of consistently high quality and am very pleased with their performance.
Since I use my Kapex for fine woodworking rather than construction, I need blades for accurate crosscutting - mostly 3/4 and 4/4 hardwoods.
For that reason, I purchased the 80T Oshlun to replace the 60T OEM Festool blade.
I compensate by slowing the cuts.
The Oshlun 80 works fine for me for crosscutting hardwoods, but would likely not do well for general construction.
For the latter, I would recommend the Oshlun 60T general purpose FesPro.
Oshlun also makes a 68 tooth FesPro for non-ferrous materials which I have never tried.
The dust collection is pretty good on a Kapex with or without Festool blades.
When I started using the Oshluns - whether on my TS55 or Kapex - the dust scatter seemed about the same as the Festool blade- if theres a difference, its slight.
If you watch someone use a Kapex, youll see that the sawdust streams into the rubber boot connected to the vacuum assembly.
From my experience, the Festool, Freud and Oshlun Festool blades all work well with the dust collection.
The dimensions of the Oshlun are close enough to the OEM Festool blade, that I didnt feel the need to reset the lasers, and havent had a problem.
I have never tried a Forrest or Tenyru blade with a Festool saw (or any other saw for that matter), so i have no way to compare them with the Oshlun or Freud.
I have several Freud blades for my track saws and think theyre great as well.
But so far as I know, Freud doesnt make blades for the Kapex.
This is my third Oshlun FesPro blade and each one has worked well - nice clean, splinter-free cuts.
Im not going to claim that they cut as well as the Festool blades, but at the price they are a great value and allow you to stretch the working life of your Festool blades.

Before I start this review, there are some inconsistencies that I want to address:First and foremost, nowhere in the product description does it state that it comes with a battery and a battery charger.
However, what was delivered to my door came in an attractive little box (entirely labeled in Chinese) that had both the flashlight, a battery, and a charger.
Not knowing this would happen, I purchasedUltraFire 18650 3000mAh 3.7V Rechargeable Li-Ion Battery (Pair) + Charger Comboin the same order, so now I have three batteries for one flashlight.
At least Ill never be without a fully-charged flashlight...!Secondly, the product is described as having three modes, and that is inconsistent with the flashlight I have.
It has a high, medium, low, fast strobe, and slow strobe.
I have some reason to believe that I am not reviewing the product as listed, but, looking through some of the reviews, there seems to be some variance in the actual product that is shipped.
Anyway, on with the review:It seems very sturdy - given the price point, though, I wouldnt recommend stress testing it.

The holster is very well designed, as it has a belt loop that closes via velcro (meaning you dont have to take off your belt to attach this to it), and it has a small triangular metal loop that one can use to clip it to, say, a bag.
Alternatively, you could attach the holster to your belt and attach a second item to the holster via the metal loop.
The holster is open on the bottom and closes with velcro, which allows you to depress the button on the bottom to turn the flashlight on before taking it out of the sheath.
This lets you turn it on, open the holster, and remove the flashlight all in one (relatively) smooth motion.
Speaking of the flashlight itself, as mentioned in several reviews, it does not automatically turn on in the same mode you turned it off in.
If you want one mode consistently, youll have to cycle through the modes every time.
Not that its too huge of a hassle unless you use it several different times in a short period.
The beam is very bright - At night, I can shine this at a tree top thats 400 feet away and I can see every detail as if it were daylight.
Also, the brightness coupled with the strobe feature makes this a fairly effective self-defense tool.
Whereas pepper spray can blow back in your face, or be entirely useless against a glasses-wearing assailant, this produces an extremely disorienting and extremely bright strobe.
No amount of eye protection or pain tolerance will keep someones retinas from whiting out.
You can, thus, temporarily blind someone and get a good run going before they have any chance to adjust.
Overall, especially for the price, Im very happy with this.
The minor mode-cycling annoyance is ignorable given that I paid less than 20 bucks for a rechargeable pocket sun / self defense tool.
Honestly, the price could increase to 30-40 and I would still be pretty pleased with the purchase.

This is one great soldering iron.
I have used several soldering irons, pencils, and guns, and this is the best one ever.
I have so much more control that I get better solder connections.
The right soldering station is an important part of having good soldering skills.
Being able to dial in exact temperatures, and to lock at a favorite temperature with included wrench, is perfect for working with sensitive electronics.
I was burning out semiconductors with my old fixed-heat 50 watt iron before; now I dont need to use a clip on the lead to protect components.
That speeds things up a lot.
There is a large variety of auxiliary soldering tips for this unit, another reason I chose it.
The provided chisel-type tip is about 1/8 wide, and its fine for most electronics work, but there are smaller chisels, awl, and tapered tips that would be better for more delicate soldering.
I ordered two smaller chisels and a pointed tip at the same time as I bought the soldering iron.

If I put the edge of the provided chisel tip in contact with the circuit board and the wire coming through the hole to be soldered, then tilt the iron up until the length of the wedge is in full contact with the wire.
This gives an instant heating effect that allows you to just touch the solder on there, and let go after a brief pause.
I get great solder joints that way.
Its a technique that works with any soldering iron with a wedge tip, but it works especially well with the Hakko.
I notice that the heating indicator turns on and off frequently and for short spells.
That seems like a good thing for keeping close to the desired temperature.
I guess not everyone does, but I like the arty color scheme.
Makes it easy to spot.
The only thing I dont like about this soldering iron is that replacement sponges cost four dollars a pop and wont last all that long.
I tend to use the sponge a lot.
I plan to experiment with cutting a household sponge to fit (will update with results).
Overall I am really pleased with this purchase and recommend it.

Pros:decent sizefast cuttingmultiple gritsflatonly need water for lubricant, saving the cost of honing oilCons:not fine enoughbacking plate too thinscratches knife bladeI have only sharpened a few knives so far, but the results were good, but not spectacular.
First off, these stones are fast cutting, and put a good utility edge on every knife I have tried them on.
The grit seems to have some edges quite a bit higher than the surface (relatively speaking) because if you are not very careful, you can scratch up the blade with them.
This seems to be improving as the stones break in, but they still will scratch the blade if you are not careful.
The stones cut quickly, but are on the coarse side, even the finest grit will cut, but not polish.
That said, if you use care, you can sharped a pretty good nick out of a blade, in a short time.
These stones are great for taking the nicks out of blades, and establishing the proper bevel.
However, to get a truly sharp edge, as in shaving sharp, you will need to follow up with something finer.
My other complaint, is that the backing plate the stones are mounted to, is quite thin, having it be an inch thick or more, would allow for easier use.
The way it is now, you have to put them on the edge of a table, or counter, to be able to lay the blade edge flat against the stone, otherwise the thickness of the handle, will not allow for it.
This is a minor quibble, because a thicker stone, would take up more storage space, and it really isnt that hard to either place them at the edge of a work surface, or on top of some kind of spacer.
I give them a 3 star performance, good but not great, but probably 4 1/2 stars in value.
Where else can you get a 3 stone diamond hone set, for under $10, let alone decent sized stones (they are about 2X8 inches in size).
I have yet to use them enough to learn about longevity, but at this price, I cant complain.
The stones are flat and true, no warpage or wobble to them.
I will end with one last comment.

The clearance holes you see, in the cutting surface, are recessed in that the diamonds are bonded to a thin piece of metal, and that metal piece has clearance holes cut into it (like most diamond stones do).

Unlike a DMT stone, which has the clearance holes filled with plastic, making for a flush surface, the plate seems to be glued on top of the plastic, so you need to watch so you dont snag the blade tip on the edge of the holes.
Not a big deal, just something to watch for.
All in all, these are a good supplement to my red and green DMT stones (fine, and ultra-fine) as the finest in this set, leaves off, about where the fine DMT stone takes over.
The DMT ultra fine stone, is fine enough to get a truly polished edge.
I was going to buy a medium DMT stone, but I got this set of 3, for about half of just one additional DMT stone would have cost, so the value is there.
Just keep in mind, for someone who wants a hair-splitting edge, you need to finish with something finer.
For utility work, like opening boxes, envelopes, peeling the insulation off wires, they do just fine, and do the job quickly.
I wanted a simple to use gadget to control our porch lights ... and this was definitely IT.

I was truly excited when this product was introduced.
It solved the issue with marking up walls when hanging things.
Or so I thought.
The idea is great.
Press the mount against the wall and push the center button in to trap the air and create suction.
Attach the level via the magnet.
I was successful in mounting it to all walls except wallpaper with a coating on it.
Flat wallpaper without any coating worked fine.
You will be able to tell if the suction is coming loose because the arrows on the button will become visible letting you know it is about to fall off.
The biggest and most important issue is that the laser is the worst I have ever used.
It only remains solid for the first few inches extending from the unit.
After that it degrades greatly and becomes more of a grainy patch than a line.
In daylight it is difficult to follow the line.
At night it is obviously more visible, but still very grainy and not much like a line at all.
For sure the laser line looks nothing like the images on here.
Laser technology in tools has been around for a long time so I really dont understand why the projection is so poor.
I also found that some stray laser reflections pointed out of the back of the unit extending downward a few inches along the wall which is somewhat distracting.
Just low quality all around.
I bought a laser level ball on here years ago that projects a solid beam for 15 plus feet, and that was only a few dollars.
There really is no excuse for this weak laser performance.
The level indicator feature is nice, however it changes from red to green without being completely centered.
You can clearly see the centering bubble is a few millimeters off to one side but still the light turns green.
This may not seem like much, but for those of us who prefer perfectly straight lines, it is.
I should have posted a picture of this but I was so disappointed in the laser quality I didnt even bother since I knew I wouldnt be keeping it.
After trying it out on three walls I noticed it left a dirty ring mark after removing it for the third time (unfortunately on a yellow wall).
So, it IS necessary to wipe off the rubber ring before installing it to the wall since it picks up dirt and then deposits on the next wall you mount it to.
My walls certainly dont appear dirty, but obviously it picked up some dirt.
I really like the mount as it will work for my old cheapo unit I bought a few years ago.
However Im not paying $30 for just a mount.
Just a note, I bought this when it first came out so hopefully they worked out the kinks by now.
Update:This thing can now be found on sale at HD for $5, so there is your answer on whether or not I got a dud.
I wish the suction cup worked better.
Like a lot of modern houses, mine in mainly textured wallboard.
The suction cup does not work at all, not even for a few seconds.
Once you put in on a smooth surface, it holds fine, but I dont normally hang pictures on my doors or jams.
If you dont mind pin holes and remember if you are off a little in your placement, another pin hole or two is in your future, then this does work.
Another complaint I have is that the level is connected via magnet and cannot be locked.
When mounted, the slightest touch will take the level out of alignment and while it is not hard to get it level (green) again, there is a little play in between the level lines.
So once it is moved, it may not be exactly in the same place again.
There should be a lock.
You also need to note that the laser only comes out of one side.
If you are using this to hang pictures along a wall you need to mount it all the way to one side so the laser shows the line on the whole wall.
You wouldnt want to start in the middle and flip it over since there is no guarantee that you will get the magnetic attachment exactly at the same level you did going the other way.
That is a horrible pun and I apologize for it.
However, this is a great product.
All of the extra features including the light and audio notifications are great and super easy.
If youre going to need to level anything and even consider hanging some things that need to be level this is a must have product.

I hate to cast dispersions on this drill, especially with all the 4 and 5 ratings, but I simply didnt like it.
In fact, I returned it after owning it for just one day.
Its bulky in your hand, and when you try to use it in gun mode the motor (which is located at the upper half of the drill) makes the drill very forward/top heavy.
This is only a 4.1 lb drill, but when youre holding it, it takes a lot out of your forearm.
Id literally rather use my RIGID impact driver (even though its heavier) because of the weight distribution.
With most drivers the battery is located at the bottom and the motor at the top (just above your hand) so that youre holding the weight of the tool with your bicep or your shoulder.
With this driver, once you bend it over to the gun position, seemingly 70% of the weight of it is now 5 inches past your hand; leaving your forearm and your wrist to do all the flexing.
In general a bicep or a shoulder is much stronger and can hold up a lot more than a wrist or a forearm; and youll feel this when you use this driver.
Maybe all drivers with the fold-over style are this way, but my next move is to get a much lighter/compact driver.
Maybe if the driver itself is shorter, thinner, and lighter, it wont matter too much if the weight all of a sudden shifts to the front when you bend it in half.
I see Makita has one of these that only weighs 1.2 lbs!
Its more than twice the price, but maybe itll solve the balancing problem.

Sadly, I cant speak to the longevity or durability of this driver (as I stated earlier, I returned it after the first day), but Ive heard good things about Hitachis quality, and the warranty is definitely second to none.
What I can tell you is that the tool isnt ergonomically sound (in my opinion) and Id advise against making the mistake of buying it.
Go find a lighter tool so that even if its top-heavy it wont matter.

Ive examined the parts that other reviewers have found to be defective or deficient.
The quality of the screw threads for the battery chamber seem to be good to me, they do not seem to suffer from any obvious quality problem in the unit I purchased.

On the other hand, the electrical contacts on both ends are soldered to circuit boards, so I can see how defects could occur at either end, solder could fail, the circuit board could crack, and any of a number of other things *could* happen there.
But to include current limiting circuitry, there must be a circuit board of some kind somewhere.
It is easy to change the mode of the flashlight, while on, press the button half-way (dont click it).
Each half-press will change the mode.
I only found one thing that I was disappointed with, that being the lack of a focus function.
The flashlight this one replaces for me, a $30 Coleman 3AAA LED Flashlight that I really liked, has a nice focusing function.
I was hoping that this would be a big step up, and be able to use as a wide-beam work light as well as a spot light...
But alas, this one has no focus option.
So I dropped it one star for that.
To be fair, there is a good reason for the lack of focus option.
This is a high-power light that can generate a lot of heat.
It would be difficult to get good coupling to dissipate that heat if the LED was on a movable mechanism, that would cause heat build-up and shorten the life of the LED.
There ARE some flashlights that do this successfully, but they have more complex mechanical construction, and cost more as a result.
The only other downside is the special battery that is required, but if I want a super-bright flashlight, I need a high current battery.
No points off for something required by the specifications.
So in summary, this is a great, very bright, flashlight in a small package.
VERY nice for the price!

There are a few things you should know.
FIRST, this seat is designed for an elongated toilet bowl.
The round bowl style would probably not work.
Since we had the round style, I did replace the toilet with a modern low flow toilet.
(needed to do that anyway, old toilet was a 5 gallon/flush unit from days of old).
I also used this opportunity to replace the water shut off to the toilet, the old shut off started leaking as soon as I tried to turn it off.
SECOND, you need a 115 volt, 15 amp electrical supply (very) near the toilet.
This can be a big deal.
I got lucky and was able to easily install a new outlet right behind the toilet.
I gave it a new dedicated 15 amp circuit.

(This step is way easier to do this once the old toilet was removed and out of the way)With the new water shut off, toilet and outlet installed, placing the new seat and hooking it up were almost trivial.
Connect the water supply to existing lines, bolt the seat down, plug it in.
Thats it!
My wife is very please with the function.
In short, if you have a modern elongated bowl toilet, with a working shut off and a nearby outlet, you can install this thing in 15 minutes, easy.

I compared this drill against a 14.4 volt Craftsman that I have used for years and the Bosch HDS181-02 compact  drill driver.
They all have the same basic features: keyless chuck, clutch, work light, two speeds and a spare battery.
However, there are some differences between them.
First, this drill is significantly heavier than the compact Bosch.
As a result, its a little tougher to use in awkward spaces, such as overhead.
However, unlike the compact version it has a very easy to use auxiliary handle that can quickly be adjusted to any position on the body of the drill, so you can drill with two hands.
Of course, this is less useful when you are trying to start a screw.
The Bosch is significantly superior to the Craftsman I have been using until now.
The Craftsman has lower voltage and lower RPMs.
Also, the Craftsmans work light is so dim that it isnt particularly useful, whereas the Boschs light provides very nice illumination if you are working in a dark area.
The Craftsman I have also does not have a hammer drill capability.
I have not used that feature yet on the Bosch, but it is supposed to make tough work, like drilling masonry, lots easier.
The Bosch also has a 1/2 inch chuck, whereas the Craftsman has only a 3/8 inch capacity.
The compact Boach has a belt clip that screws on to the base of the drill, but this model does not have a belt clip.
The Craftsman has two features that the Bosch does not have.

It has two self-store slots for the screwdriver bits, whereas the screwdriver bit for the Bosch simply sits in the bottom of the case, and is almost guaranteed to get lost if you dont have a case for your bits.
The Craftsman also has two leveling bubbles -- one on the top and one on the back -- so if you want a perfectly horizontal or vertical hole, you are more likely to get it with the Craftsman.
On the whole, I recommend the Bosch  over the Craftsman for its extra power, good work light longer battery life and convenience of use.

Washington, D. C.--The 100 Watt incandescent bulb, phased out for the sin of consuming too much energy and giving off too much heat, died on New Years Day, 2012, at the age of 132.
He was survived (at least temporarily) by his cousins, the 75 watt, 60 watt and 40 watt incandescent.
He will be remembered fondly for his warm, homey glow, his gentle cooperation with dimmer switches and his flexibility and usefulness in all indoor-and-outdoor light fixtures.

In the wintertime in the colder areas of the United States, including New England and the Pacific Northwest, he provided not just light but a steady warmth that reduced the heating bills by just a bit.
He had a simple, aesthetically pleasing design, so iconic it became known as the very symbol for ideas.
It would be an exaggeration to say the 100 Watt ever had any ideas of his own, despite being a symbol of them.
Rarely could you find a more unpretentious fellow.
Inexpensive, predictable and harmless--if a tad boring.
For a glass globe, he was fairly hardy and wouldnt break that easily if you you squeezed him when twisting him in the socket.

One of my favorite flashlights is my trusty SureFire P9...
Ive had it for years, and its been a great product: built like a tank, good quality light and fairly good battery life.
After a few years of use, the bulb finally went on my P9, and I decided to try a few alternatives other than the SureFire P90 product it came with.
Of the alternatives, this one seemed the best.
Although its not made by SureFire, the fit was precise, and if anything, the construction quality seemed better than the original.
The light output is quite a bit brighter... my P9 went from "bright" to "dazzling".
Overall, the light is slightly bluer and more daylight like, with a strong but small central area surrounded by a broad beam.
Its easily enough to light your way outdoors, and for folks like me who dont see as well in the dark as I used to, its  terrific.
I was worried about two things, but neither proved to be the case.
First, the P9 uses high capacity CR123A batteries, and if you leave the stock bulb on for a while, the batteries tend to get quite hot, to the point where the flashlight is uncomfortable to handhold.
I feared the brighter bulb would require more juice, and the flashlight would get even hotter, but that hasnt been the case.
Still gets warm, but certainly no more so than with the stock bulb installed.
Second, I was concerned that battery life would be less with the brighter bulb, but again, my fears proved unfounded.
Those CR123A batteries are expensive, but Im happy to say that battery life isnt significantly worse due to the brighter bulb.
Overall, this makes a great flashlight terrific, and its definitely worth a look if you have a flashlight that can use it.
Definitely recommended!

Ive used this type of solder sucker for many years.
My previous one, made of metal, occasionally would catch the skin on my finger.
This one is a great deal for the price, especially if you have Amazon Prime (costs less than a Big Mac with trimmings).
The only other options for solder removal are solder wick or a much more expensive soldering station with vaccum removal.
I dont like solder wick because I think it can overheat a joint.
The expensive soldering station is just too expensive for a hobbyist like me.
There are a two things to be aware of with a tool like this.
First of all, there is the possibility of solder splashes being deposited on your circuit card.
When I was repairing military avionics, we were not allowed to use these type of devices.
Unless the solder you suck is removed before the next use, the solder, in the form of small splashes can be sprayed on the circuit when you use the tool again.
This was really not a problem for military electronics because the circuit cards are coated with a protecterant material, humiseal.
Even as a hobbyinst, I havent had any problems.
But, I routinely compress and operate the sucker into a waste can or trash bag after every use.
That eliminates most of the splashes.
Secondly, these tools have a recoil.
That is, when the plunger reaches its end, the tip comes back and impacts the circuit card.
If the circuit card is unconstrained, it will bounce across your table/bench.
This has never been a real problem but you should be aware of it.
Lately, I have been using a Panavise to secure a circuit card before soldering/unsoldering and this has worked well.
I dont see how you can find anything cheaper to do this job.

They list 24 things you shouldnt do, with some redundancy (for instance: you arent supposed to touch the bulbs with your hands (?
)AND you arent supposed to touch the bulbs with wet hands).

Than too the bulbs are not supposed to be used in an enclosed fixture or even a partially enclosed fixture (I would think that if one is so poor that one has bare lights in bare sockets or hanging from pendents mounted to the ceiling, one isnt shelling out ~$10 per bulb.
)These lamps are not instant on - there is a slight, but noticeable delay between switching on and light coming on.
Only about 250 milliseconds.
When cold that time is more like a half second.

(if the switch ever fails on my refrigerator lights I should know it - seems inconsequential - but when youve got 160 watts of lamps in a refer that only eats ~200 watts when the compressor runs, it would easily double the running cost - paying to heat the air and paying to cool it, that delay should alert me to a switch malfunction)Any of the bulbs I bought would be excellent for use in desk lamps, or reading lamps - providing the bulb faces in the direction the light is needed.

They are working very well in the refrigerator too, although I would question the economy of spending $40 on lamps that only come on for a minute or two a day - even in a refrigerator that has to pay twice for the energy wasted.
I like it, but objectively speaking, it  makes no sense.
One thing about all LED lamps is that there is no standardization on life expectancy tests.
While most LEDs dont burn out unless they are subject to too much voltage or heat, they do have a half-life and that varies greatly with manufacturing quality control.
When they quote 10-20 years they dont generally mean 24/7 operation; and then they mean that the light output will drop to some fraction of what it was when the lamp was new.
With increased heat the LED life expectancy will be less.
Ideally they should be de-rated, for heat - reducing the current in the lamp to compensate for the reduced cooling of a hot environment.
(so a dimmer - something these lamps wont tolerate, may make a lot of sense with some other led lamp)Im a retired electrical engineer and a LED junky.

These are great switches, and appear to be exactly the same as those that came on my more powerful large power tools.
You can use these switches for a number of great things where safety is an issue.
In my case, I am using one for a 3.5 hp router that I have mounted in a router table I just made.
Another, I am using to replace the switch on a brand new floor mounted belt and disc sander.
Nothing wrong with the switch on the new sander, I just want the safety that a magnetic switch provides, including the large stop paddle.
The third, I will mount to my workbench wired to a standard 15 amp outlet so I can plug in any tool I want and have easy safe control.
For those who complained about no wiring diagram being included,  I understand to some degree.
But keep in mind that most switches include a wiring diagram right on the switch itself, including these switches.
You can look on the side of the actual body of the switch, and the wiring instructions are right there.

Granted, you need to have a basic understanding of electricity to understand what the diagram means, but if you do not have a basic understanding of wiring, then perhaps you should not be doing anything regarding electrical wiring of this nature.
Finally, I saw one comment here that mentioned that these switches were relay switches???
I am sure this poster was confused.
These are actual 110 volt, 15 amp, magnetic switches.
They can be used exactly like any other switch, but have one additional safety feature.
If power is lost through a power outage, or circuit breaker tripping, when power is restored the switch remains off until the green on button is pressed.
This prevents a very dangerous situation that can happen with power tools.
Imagine that you are running a router or saw and a breaker trips or you lose power.
You leave the tool thinking it is off, but it is not off if you are using a standard switch.
So when the power is restored, the tool once again has power, and can start all by itself causing a potentially lethal situation with a runaway tool.
A MAGNETIC SWITCH PREVENTS THIS DANGEROUS SITUATION.
This switch IS a magnetic switch.
Anyway, great switches at a great price if you know what they are and what they do.

If you wanted to cover 24VAC, 120-377VAC, and 480 VAC with one product youd need 3 p/ns to put on your shelf in inventory.
"Thats 3 times the amount of inventory Im willing to stock for a well made 1/2"" nipple motion sensor to cut lighting costs."
Cutting lighting costs is not an easy task - motion sensors alone dont often handle the whole problem.

Nitpick #2 - on most of my installs I look at the IP number (e. g. IP-65 IP-66 and others.

"I was hoping this would make painting fences and our detached garage a piece of cake but ""piece of cake"" was apparently not in the design specs when this gun was developed."
To be clear Ive worked with spray guns before as did my dad who also tried this gun out for me.
He owned his own custom furniture business for 25 years.
We have sprayed too many cabinets, chairs and tables to count.
Lacquer (clear, black and white), paint and stain all went through the same gun.
Clean up involved re-attaching the gun to our vat of thinner and running it for 30 seconds or until the stream was clear, done.
As soon as you open the instructions and begin reading youll understand quickly why this is a mess.
First of all you have to thin the paint or product your pushing through it but there are no indications as to ratio or even just consistency.
So right off the bat as you start spraying it becomes a trial and error process to get an even spray.
Why the product needs to be thinned is beyond me but it has to be as you might find out if you try pushing it without enough thinner.
Once you get it relatively close (best guess is the best you can do here) the sprayer still manages to spit globs, even with a vigorous stirring.
Clean up is just as difficult.
Things need to be taken apart and cleaned individually...
Im getting frustrated just typing this.
"They advertise a ""quick-clean"", maybe I did it wrong but I could not get this thing to clean the system thoroughly."
It has to be taken apart to get a good cleaning.

It could be the fact that I have so much experience with the old school compressor style sprayer that Im just fumbling this thing big time, but by looking at some of the other reviews Im getting the feeling that Im not alone here.

My opinion; Every home workshop should have a compressor, if you have a compressor you may as well just get a simple compressor driven sprayer and the attachments to hook it up to your cans of paint, stain, lacquer, etc.
Learn to keep a steady wrist, time your passes evenly and keep a consistent distance.
If you can do that you can save your money for a real spray gun.
This thing is a gimmick in my opinion.

I live on a ranch and have a remote gate on our property that opens from remote controls in our vehicles.
We installed a keypad so that visitors could come through the gate, but at night, the keypad was tricky to see in order for someone to punch in our code.
I ordered one of these units and installed it above the keypad and it not only illuminated the pad, but for several feet away.

And several times when people have come to visit, they have asked if this device takes their picture or is a theft/crook device of some sort.
When the light comes on, it does suggest that it might be a sensor of some kind and that indeed it is either warning the home owner or capturing the image of the person who triggered the light.
I liked this solar light so much that I bought two more to install on the gate, away from the keypad.
They are sensitive enough to detect human traffic from several feet away, and they work well in "seeing" my car from about 8 feet away.
The amount of illumination from the tiny light is very surprising and I am satisfied with all three of my lights.
These lights would work very well for someone having an outside set of stairs that need to be climbed at night because the amount of light they emit is very generous for such a small device.
One word of advice though... there is a tiny metal probe that must be gentle pushed into a small orifice in order to turn these units on.
If you overlook inserting the "tool" and gently pressing what must be an "on/off" button inside the unit, it will not function as it supposed to.
The "tool" is small and easy to lose.
I dropped one into grass and wasnt able to find it, but since I had two spares, I was able to turn the device on.
A small set of screws and plastic anchors come with this so you can drill a hole into a wall (like sheet rock) and attach it.
I didnt need these and elected to use self-drilling screws through the metal post holding the keypad.

I didnt see any provision to allow for removing the original batteries once they have exhausted their service life, so these lights will eventually be "throw-aways" some day, like it seems is so much of the trinkets that are being made in China and that we import.
Other than my "negative" slant on the disposable aspect of this light, I am pleased with all three of my purchases.
I remodeled our kitchen last year and replaced the counter tops, backsplash, sink, faucet etc.
I bought two of these Newer Technology Power2U wall outlets to install.
During the remodel, I added under cabinet LED lighting and replaced all the gang boxes for wall outlets and light switches.
The gang boxes I replaced were single gang boxes (made for one outlet or switch).
It was IMPOSSIBLE to make the Power2U fit in the new gang box.
Gang boxes are a standard size so switch and outlet manufacturers like Cooper and Leviton know the size of the cavity their products will be fitted to.
This Power2U does not conform to this standard.
It might work if you use a triple gang box (made for three switches or outlets) and placed the Power2U in the middle.
The width and depth of the Power2U is much, much larger than the outlet you will remove.
Consequently, it will not fit.
This may be the reason you dont see any pictures of the outlet compared to a standard outlet.
Leviton now makes a similar outlet that will work correctly, though you will only have one 120V outlet since the 2 USB charging ports occupy the 2nd 120V space.
While I didnt use this product because it wouldnt fit, I did play with the sliding doors concealing the USB ports.
The doors are not easy to use.

They require a fingernail to open and close and would be awkward if you were holding a device and trying to plug in at the same time, or the outlet was in a difficult place to use your fingernail to open the tiny sliding doors.

We bought a fixer upper house in January 2012.
Most of it was practically a gut job - new bathroom tile, new stained cabinetry in the kitchen, new flooring, carpeting, paint throughout - and lots of chemically odors too.
When I was wondering what we were going to do about the new house smells, it didnt occur to me that I could get something to fit my air system that might help.
I just hoped time would dissipate the worst of it.
We havent moved in yet and Ive been hesitant to put up my curtains and move in the furniture because Im afraid anything fabric will just absorb the odors and theyll end up lasting even longer.
My husband installed the filter and we left the new house.
When I returned about a day and a half later, I was ecstatic to note that much of the worst of the chemically odors has gone.

Im very happy with this product so far!Thank you Amazon and Filtrete for giving me the opportunity to try this.

Im a handyman and aspiring, (wannabe?...
haha) electrician.
Roughly 50% of my power tool needs on projects are covered using my 11 M12 tools.
Every so often though I work on assembling large closet systems and large IKEA furniture.
My M12 right angle driver works well on these jobs but I also use it in tandem with the 3/8 drill for pre-drilling & driving in series and I prefer it for most of the medium sized fasteners.
In short, I was using THAT tool disproportionately more than all of my other M12s.
I bought this to take some of the load off the right angle drill/driver.

I went w/ the 3/8 drive because if I need to adapt DOWN to 1/4 I can use the included adapter and actually gain power as opposed to adapting 1/4 UP to 3/8 where I have a LOSS of power/strength/torsion etc.
This ratchet also has 5 FT. lbs.
more torque that the 1/4 drive M12.

Some may not realize that this (and ratchets in general) is actually a quasi/mini-impact wrench that requires less radial clearance than a hand ratchet to get  a GOOD turn because it DOES all the turning!
Heck even w/ a dead battery the ratcheting assembly still works and we can use the tool as a regular hand ratchet or even to fine tune a fastener by hand.
The LED shines right on the money even w/ an 2 extension.
The Red Lithium battery included with the kit provides solid run-time and the pouch/case is rugged enough & w/ plenty of storage space ... Really cool kit for mechanics, handymen and assemblers.
These little gizmos do work just as described.

This is a basic lab coat.
This might be standard, but I really liked that the pockets werent actual pockets, but instead allowed access to your pants pockets.
This light is ASTONISHINGLY bright on High mode, especially for a 1xAAA battery flashlight, and it works great on Eneloop rechargeable batteries.
I dont need go past medium brightness for most tasks.
High mode is useful for blinding the bad guys or for checking the backyard for skunks before I let the dogs out for their pre bedtime potty.
It has a useful range of about 100 feet or so on High.
When it is dark, even the Low mode will let me see pretty well out to about 15 feet!
And it is easy to change between the 3 light levels just by twisting the head of the flashlight.
And, after having been off for about 3 seconds, it automatically starts up again in Low mode, which is great for preserving (at least some of) my night vision.
I really like how simple, light weight and compact it is.
And it is small, the length of a Chapstick tube but smaller around.
I took the pocket clip off as I never used it, since I usually carry it in my front pants pocket.

A note on pants pocket carry; make sure you have the flashlights head loosened enough so that you can not push it down and have the light turn on, or you may end up accidentally running down the battery while it is in your pocket.
The included key chain with a spring clip is handy for me as well, since I can clip it on a belt loop or a zipper pull and carry it conveniently that way, too.

And I discovered another way to use it, which is (with the head loosened just enough that the light is off) holding it by the head between my thumb and index finger with the butt of the flashlight braced in the web between my thumb and index finger.
I just have to pull back slightly on the head to turn it on, and can change modes quickly that way also.
And my little finger is small around enough that I can just slip the clip over my little finger like a ring.
That way I can let go of the light and use both hands for something, without dropping the light.
I REALLY like this iTP A3 EOS Upgraded Version AAA Keychain LED Flashlight, and plan on getting some more, both for myself and to give as gifts.
HIGHLY RECOMMENDED.
NOTE: This flashlight DOES NOT come with a battery included.
UPDATE: After 2 mos.
of regular frequent use, this light is still working great.
Im using an eneloop AAA rechargeable battery in it, and have not had to recharge it yet!
I put the pocket clip back on, to serve as an anti-roll feature.
When Olight bought iTP, they discontinued the iTP brand and had their own (made in China) version of the iTP made, which they call the Olight i3 EOS, or i3s EOS.
This was in some ways a step backwards in my opinion, becaust the Olight comes on in High mode 1st, rather than Low mode for the iTP.

The Olight also has a lower light output and much shorter run time on High, while the Medium level is 2lm brighter with longer run time, and  the Low level is MUCH lower with only a slightly longer run time.
Plus, Olight added a strobe mode, which seems to me to be about useless in a light this small and with such low lumen output.
And the Key Chain of the Olight does not seem to be as sturdy, and the Clip is not as easy to use.
The only advantages I can see the Olight having are that it can tail stand, and the pocket clip is reversible.
All in all, I personally prefer the iTP A3 EOS Upgrade Version.
AND, the iTP is less expensive, too!

I bought this digital timer 6 months ago to replace a 7 year-old mechanical timer and this is an excellent digital timer.
The major differences between this digital timer and the mechanical timer are:1.
It has a battery backup to keep accurate time in case of power loss.2.
This timer offers (20) twenty precise on/off settings per day which far exceeds my requirements.
You can even configure it for any day or group of days of the week.3.
It looks much better and more technologically advanced than a mechanical timer.
Despite these advantages, I also bought the same mechanical timer replacement to use as back up since the last one lasted 7 years.
I was able to properly program the timer in 10 minutes just by playing with it.
The instructions are not 100% accurate but the timer is not that hard to program.
I have read bad reviews about the reliability of this timer but I have NOT had any problems using this timer.
This timer has functioned flawlessly for several months now without ANY problems.

Everyone needs to be aware that any digital timer will reset itself (or lose the set program) if AC power is lost for an extended period of time that exceeds the backup battery capability (the battery backup will only keep the timer powered for a certain period of time before it is drained of power itself in the event of extended power loss).
This timer keeps very accurate time for me and does exactly what it is programmed to do.
Therefore, I give this timer 5 stars because of its price and reliability.
If it lasts as long as my mechanical timer did then I will be a very happy camper.
It is still a great timer and well worth the low price.

The only other drawback is the light beam cannot be focused.

UPDATE 10/5/2013- My second light which came this week had the extension tubes screwed together so tightly I had a lot of trouble separating them, and I almost thought someone had machined the light incorrectly.
I thought I would need to use the full length with 3 18650 batteries.
The second problem I encountered was that the switch did not cause the light to come on when I pressed it.
Bumping / Tapping the light made the light come on and changed the mode - erratically.
The SOS was flaky.
Finally I discovered that the piece containing the LEDs had not been screwed down tightly.
I turned it tightly - about 5 revolutions, and the light works as it should have worked out of the box.
SOS is 3 short-3 long-3 short as it should be.
The light has no defects, just poor quality control during assembly.
For those who receive a new light that will not turn on, I would recommend disassembling the head of the light completely and ensuring that everything is tightened as it is reassembled.
Just dont touch the shiny reflective surfaces of the head under the glass.
One interesting phenomenon is that in a dark room, you may notice light coming from the 3 LEDs for a few seconds after it is turned off until the energy in the circuit dissipates.
So far these lights work fine, and the price was good.
Buying in bulk on Amazon saves a lot of money compared to purchasing in store, so I am happy with my purchase.

This satin-nickle, keyed lockset will look good on any door.
It is a Sclage lockset, which in my experience is the best brand for high quality at a reasonable price.
What sets this lockset apart from the typical keyed lockset is the built in alarm.
The alarm has 3 settings so you can decide how the alarm will be of most benefit for you.
The activity alert is best for the home that wants to know when someone in the house, such as a young child, tries to open the door.
Every time the door is opened, the alarm beeps twice.
Tamper alert sounds an alarm sounds for 15 seconds whenever anyone moves the lever (door knob).
Works in both the lock and unlock mode.
The alarm is 90 db, same as a smoke alarm.
So that you will not trigger the alarm every time you enter or leave, there is a 60-second delay.
Forced entry alert is a 3-minute alarm when significant force pushes againt the door.
The sound is a steady, shrill siren of 90 db.
The alarm is pre-set for forced entry, but a clear explanation is given on how to change the setting.
From the outside the lock looks like any other, the inclusion of an alarm is not indicated.
The warning light and button for testing and programing the alarm is on inside the door portion of the lockset.
Instructions for installing and setting up the alarm are easily understood and provided in both English and Spanish in the Users Guide and accompanying diagrams.
This was useful in my case because the maintenance man where I live does better in Spanish than English.
Everything needed to install and program the lock are included, except for a screwdriver.

Just light, which is what I wanted.

It can be operated in a pinch with a single AA battery at reduced light level, but I bought the package of two Ultrafire LC14500 rechargeable batteries with a wall chargerUltraFire 14500 1200mah 3.6V Rechargeable Li-Ion Battery (Pair) + Charger Combo.

The charger and two batteries cost more than the flashlight but you keep one charged and the other in the flashlight; it works about an hour on a full charge and seems to hold a charge well when not in use.
This light really does fit in my Levis pocket, quite easily.
The clip came off after a few weeks of heavy use but I dont miss it.
The key here is value... you buy this light and the 2 batteries with a charger and youre barely out $20 for a very compact, bright light.
Add a second flashlight and youre under $30 for the package.

I had a remodel job to do which involved removing tile from a concrete floor for new fixtures so I needed a roto hammer.
That is why I ordered this device.
The compact design meant that I could get into some tight spots to remove the old tile that would have required using a regular hammer and chisel otherwise.
Here is what I liked about this product:1.
High power battery that lasted for the entire tile removal process and also for chipping out a wider drain opening in the concrete floor.2.
Compact size that allowed me to work in a tight floor space area without having to resort to hand tools.3.
Battery and charger are compatible with my other Bosch tools.4.
Sturdy carrying case that allows you to pack several bits, the charger, and extra battery and such into a tool bag that can fit into tight spaces (the trunk of my car with the other tools).
What I did not like:1.
The tool had grease all over the battery when it arrived.
I presume this was from the grease that is packed in the tool head and that the box must have gotten hot in shipment or storage before it arrived at my place.
A Note to keep in mind:  This tool requires SDS Plus bits!!!!!!!
No, you cannot use a normal concrete bit designed for a drill in this tool!
First, the bit will not fit and second it is NOT designed to take the impact!!
Also, keep in mind the instructions to LUBRICATE a bit BEFORE inserting it into this tool!!
Also, keep your bits clean!This is an excellent tool that is well made and easy to use.
Just ensure that you follow the directions for using this tool if you have not used a roto hammer before.
I would certainly recommend it to anyone having a need for this type of tool.

This is the best LED bulb Ive tried.
Positives:+ Very good color.
A little brighter white than the warm white CFL it replaced, but indistinguishable unless youre looking very closely with a traditional bulb and this LED side by side.
Much better than the early vintage of LEDs, which were too bluish for my taste.+ Excellent form factor.
Exact same size and shape as a traditional bulb, so it fits in any fixture that would take an old fashioned incandescent bulb.+ Bright.
In side-by-side tests, puts out about as much light as a 60-75 watt incandescent bulb.+ Instant brightness (unlike some CFLs, which take a while to reach full brightness).+ Super efficient.
11 watts puts out the equivalent light of a 75 watt traditional bulb.
Nice.+ The bulb part of the bulb stays pretty cool, although the white area between the metal screw base and the hemispherical bulb gets hot enough to burn your fingers.
The only downside:- Wicked expensive.
If it really lasts two decades, I guess I could make back the investment, especially with interest rates so low.
But for now, a $2 20-watt CFL puts out the same light.

If Im doing the calculations correctly, the CFL uses about $2 more per year in electricity and would have to be replaced a few times over 20 years, which means the LED and CFL are just about the same cost over 20 years.
But a lot can happen in 20 years.
So, although Im glad I tried this bulb to see that its a great substitute for incandescents and CFLs, I doubt Ill replace all my existing bulbs until the price comes down a bit.
I know theres a chicken and egg problem here (the prices wont come down unless the volume ramps up because we all buy), but at forty bucks a bulb I cant afford to do a wholesale swap.

Some words of advice on LED bulbs:I recently switched out every bulb in my house to LED bulbs.
Originally I thought I could easily switch out every light in my house to the same LED bulb, but I quickly learned that not all LED bulbs are created equal or are honest in their claims.
Each fixture in my home has a different brand of bulb, since every bulb produces a differently quality of light.
I had grown accustom to a specific quality of light in various areas of my house, which made picking the right LED very challenging.
Outfitting your house with LED bulbs requires you to analyze where you want the most light and where you need mood lighting.
Many LED bulbs produce great dim mood lighting at very low prices.
These are areas of your house are where you can save money when buying LED bulbs.
Multi-directional bulbs cost significantly more, so be very specific where you need that kind of bulb before buy one for every fixture in your house.
Unlike incandescent lights, most LED bulbs have a slight delay when turning on.
Once on the bulb is instantly bright, unlike fluorescence bulbs that take time to warm up.
I found that some places of my house, I needed that instant on from the LED bulb (example: closet or bathroom).
A good rule of thumb, most LED bulbs that claim to be dimmable usually are instant on too.
I dont have any dimmers in my house, but the instant on was important.
Not only do LED bulbs use less electricity, but they put off almost no heat.
This has made a huge difference in the temperature of my house, especially during the hot Texas summer.
Fun fact: 80% of the energy used by an incandescent bulb produces heat not light.
The Moen S3870 is a slide bar shower, which means that it has an adjustable bar that sits against the front wall of the shower, allowing for height adjustment of the shower head.

This isnt something I need, but I did find the slide bar allowed me to raise the shower head several inches above my existing shower head, and the extra few inches make a fairly significant change.
Installation was somewhat easy, even with the poor instructions.
I installed it in a standalone shower and had it running in less than ten minutes.
It is very simple to change the spray pattern.
With traditional handhelds, you have to turn a dial, which Ive always found annoying.
With the Moen, there are four different massage settings on each side of the shower head, which makes switching flow patterns easier.
Unfortunately, I found most of the flow patterns to be pretty worthless because of poor water pressure.
Usually you can manually fix this by removing a washer inside the shower head, but I couldnt figure out a way to do that with the Moen.
My only other complaint is the chrome finish on it, which looks okay, but for this price I would expect a satin nickel finish and something that feels a bit more substantial.

These flameless candles are the best on the market.
Pros:+ Brighter than most flameless candles.
Was useful during the power outage after Hurricane Sandy+ Mild vanilla scent.
This is as close to unscented as it gets (for now).

Flameless candles usually have an extra strong scent to make up for not having a real flame to help disapate scent.+ Runs for 75 continuous hours on one watch battery as claimed.+ Realistic flicker pattern.+ Cool to touch and safe around pets.

Cons:- One of the candles had a chipped edge and package was new sealed from manufacturer.- Although brighter than most other flameless candles on the market, one of these still did not equal the light output of a single tealight.
These flameless votives are realistic, non-smelly, safe and easy to use.
I was very comfortable leaving them on around the house overnight unattended with multiple house guests and animals during the Hurricane.
It was used as a nightlight by the sink in the bathroom and at the top of the steps and around corners to help guide the way.
