This is the best wood repair stuff on earth.
When it dries it acts just like fresh hardwood.
It expands and contracts just like the surrounding wood.
It needs to be painted.
I have used this to fill a 2 1/8 inch diameter x 2 inch deep  hole in a door from a deadbolt that was removed.
I cut a round filler that took up about 80% of the volume, then packed the rest of the hole with this stuff.
Several layers - drying between each layer.
Then sanded flush with the surrounding wood door.
After painting you could never tell there used to be a deadbolt.
And this stuff is strong.
You can drill it, screw into it, sand it, cut it - it acts just like wood.
Smell is horrible until dry.
It takes about 10 minutes to set up so it can be moulded (like clay), and then another 30 minutes until it is hard as a rock.
Like Bondo for wood.
Works great.
Just wish it were easier to find.
I wonder if it has been discontinued or something.
Nobody seems to stock it anymore.

Overall I am extremely satisfied with this tool.

Bought these for my boat to replace hot halogen and to save some battery.

This is one of the few solar lights that have a remote solar panel so you can mount them for optimal charging.
I use 2 of these to light up house numbers where there is no (other) light source at night.
The light intensity is a average and is comparable to older type LEDs that by July 2013 newer lights are brighter and more efficient.
Do not expect anything near LED flashlight intensity.
If used to read house numbers, your digits and background must have high contrast (white numbers/black background), or you will have to move much closer to decipher the numbers.
These are okay if you dont require bright light.
Their best applications are where your intentions are limited to highlighting an area, not for pointing out details.
Newer (design) and brighter LED solar spotlights are available and Im eventually switching to them (but will cost 3-4 times more).
Addition:  Still working well after 4 months, no problems.
2 major flaws: clicky switch and pocket clipClicky switch: this is a well documented issue with this light.
When you have the aluminum cover installed it will turn on really easily in your pocket.
Can you say, dead batteries and a warm leg?
Solution: remove the aluminum part that covers a rubber boot.
This will solve the problem but create an odd form factor.
I dont care for this too much but I did it and it works.
Pocket Clip: A not so well documented issue.
The pocket clip does a few things,1) it will lose its shape and stop holding onto your pocket after about 2 weeks or so.
solution: take it off every week- 2 weeks and bend it, reassemble and get going.

really annoying because it is something that could be easily avoided if the manufacturer would have put more money into the materials of the clip.2) the clip will grab onto the inner seem of your shirt and rip threads.
The clip itself has a rather large flange to aid in sliding onto your pocket.
This "flange" will grab your shirt seems and rip threads, as I said.
This coupled with a pocket clip that loses its strength really fast = a flashlight outside of your pocket hanging by the threads of your shirt.
ANNOYING and very close to a lost light.
BESIDES the 2 major flaws, the light is great.

This is my fourth hot water dispenser over the last 30 years.
One Kenmore, 2 Insinkerators, and now this Waste King.
The instructions need serious work, but youll figure it out.
Its worth it, the quality of the faucet and hoses are so much better than the overpriced Insinkerators.
If youre not comfortable with plumbing projects, you might want to skip this one.
You will need two mounting screws, plus plastic anchors if youre going into drywall.
Youll need a 3/8 to 1/4 straight tubing connector either plastic push on or copper with inserts and ferrules.
Youll need a short piece of 3/8: OD  hard plastic or copper tubing to connect the 3/8 Waste King cold water supply line to your straight tubing adapter.
You wont need either the adapter or the tubing if your supply line is 3/8 but most are 1/4.
Youll need a basin wrench and it is still difficult to tighten the faucet nut; the nut is very close the tubing, very little clearance.
The instructions dont show the fitting that goes on top of the tank on the center pipe that converts it so the supplied tubing from the faucet will fit.
Its a compression fitting with a make end that matches the end on the faucet and sort of has the shape of a Russian Orthodox spire.
The instructions dont mention it either.
If you lose it unpacking, you have a problem that will require a creative solution.
At least a couple of reviewers clearly did not understand that as indicated by their frustration trying to get the 1/4 hose over the 3/8 center pipe.
There are no instructions for how the ferrules work; theyre standard but if you dont know, youll have to figure out which way the taper goes.
Im done, Im happy, if its still working in 5 years Ill be even happier.

Once I fully charged the Nest it was able to function now perfectly without losing connection for the last couple months.
I found that it only maintained my charge.
Minor flaw to note, you might have to buy a USB charger for the  Nest because the low voltage connection might not bring it up to full charge.
I have also found the emails that the device sends monthly helpful in monitoring energy usage.
I simultaneously set the max and min temperatures while the device senses me in the house and I also set a broader temperature range for when it can tell that no one is home.
I had read that this was invented by former Apple engineers and you can tell by the build quality and ease of ease it just might have been.
I read some complaints about the software on the smartphone that I cant find or they have drastically improved it, as I find it mostly easy to use and seamless.
You can get most of the functionality directly from the smartphone controls.
I have a single zone system with both A/C and heat.
The Learning Thermostat changed the way I look at home climate control.
Too soon to tell; for convenience of remote access alone that maybe a high price to pay.
Am I getting $249 of value from it?
Did notice on a couple of occasions that temp showing on the device was very high and it seems to be the base that gets hot (it does have electronics in there too from what I can gather).
Once it has gone through its learning any changes you make carry less weight unless they are repeated often enough for the thing to learn the new behavior.
Once the Nest has learnt our pattern of daily activity it works well so make sure the first week you install it is your typical activity pattern week, otherwise it learns the wrong pattern.
Also not sure about the green leafs you earn etc and their value as a motivational tool to lower energy usage.
The monthly energy report that is emailed was interesting at first but now seems to be of diminishing value.
The Nest device is great looking, solidly built, works as advertised, is easy to install and its very convenient to access the thermostat from any of my mobile devices.
Used this when cleaning inside a chimney firebox.
Worked well, very bright, long battery life and you can angle the light.
I was wondering how they got a 14 inch desk lamp in a 10 inch box.
When I opened it I got may answer, it folds up easy and holds its shape.
Some flex pieces on lamps and other devices, look like theyd break if you twist them too far, but this one seems pretty good.
Plus, they didnt have to make it super strong to hold a heavy weight like most of these desk lamps.
The head is about as small as the base, which is a nice thing too, as it does not take up much space on a small desk, another plus.
The LED technology makes for a very bright light, that on my books, did not seem to give me any eye fatigue that Ive suffered with some florescents, and some high intensity incandescents in the past.
Another good thing, the life expectancy of the lamp source for this is a very long time, and given the price of this, it makes the lamp a throw-a-way, years from now when it finally burns out.
Most hi-intensity incandescents of the past get too hot, and the bulb burns out too soon, many times, the propriatary replacements cannot be found, and the fitting will not accept some standard bulb.
This will never happen with this lamp.
Strangely, when reading the printed instructions (mimimal as you would think), I saw a switch on the base.
The lamp I had didnt have one there, so I scratched my head a while.
Was it one of those touch lamps?
Could be, but usually they have a polished metal surface, and this did not.
Then, I noticed a small button on the underside of the light sourse ring.
I plugged in the transformer, and pushed it, (the tiny switch) and behold we have light.

This last bit I liked a lot too, Im always straining to find the rotery switch on my reading lamp, the base is so big, and I often park a soda or a remote control on the base, then I have to feel for the switch, usually knocking something out of place.
With this lamp, I know the switch is right on the light source here, so its easy, getting there is out of the way, an easy reach to turn it on and off.

Many of my past twist lamps, due to the head weight, only hold a few positions without wanting to move, this head is so light that the twist stem can hold it in most any position, so I get exactly the light I want, on my book for reading or writing.
This is a great lamp, and not too expensive, so I give it my rare, highest rating as a product.
It is excellent, in price and performance both, would that all products be as good!

This Rotozip made short work of some detail cutting I needed to do on tile for my shower.
I used theRotoZip XB-FT1 1/4-Inch Floor Tile XBIT, 1-Packbit and was able to essentially plunge cut holes for the pluming to come through the tile.
The result was a very clean finished look with only a small area left to caulk around the pipes.
As for cutting, with the right wheel this tool will cut through almost anything.
The X-bit wood wheel that comes in this set is a hot knife through butter for wood cuts.
That being said, cutting straight or level freehand has been impossible for me beyond the smallest and simplest cuts.
Even cutting a metal closet rod down to size with the included metal cutting abrasive wheel yielded an end that was uneven freehand no matter how careful I thought I was.
The reason it was so difficult was that the tool could not cut straight through the rod (the blade is not deep enough) so I needed to cut all of the way around it.
The reason I mention this detail is the picture of the guy cutting the pluming under the sink in the product description is a joke - he is not going to buzz right through that pipe.
Plus the end piece he has on that Rotozip is not included in this setup.
The one included here is at 90 degrees for the wheel.
But setting up some sort of guide for accurate cutting is essential for most tools anyway.
The bottom line is that this Dremel on steroids got the job done for me on tile, metal and drywall (I quickly cut two holes for in-ceiling speakers).
One final thought, sit down when you go to purchase bits, wheels and accessories for your Rotozip.
Xbits and X-wheels are not cheap.
And some of the many accessories available cost half as much as the tool.
But at least one of the specialty handles is really worth the price.
I have theRotoZip JSH5 Jig Saw handle Kitand it really makes cutting easier for some situations.
I am replacing my old, but still working shower head with this Detla shower head.
With this price, I would have expected it to be all metal.
But its not.
It looks like metal, but its actually chrome-plated plastic.
However, all of the fittings, including the hose, are metal.
Just the shower head itself and the hand held shower are plastic.
Installation is pretty straightforward.
Actually, in my case, getting the old one out takes some effort.
The separate hand-held unit has a very solid feel as it snaps in and out of the main unit.
The handheld unit is very lightweight.
The metal hose has some weight that keeps the hose from getting tangled and twisted.
The main shower head is 6 wide and it sprays water in only one pattern.
A knob on the side of main shower head controls whether water comes out of the base only, the handle only, or both.
Then a push button on the handle controls the 4 different spray settings.
I like how quick and easy it is to toggle between full-spray and tiny trickle, thats a great way to save water.
My daughter complains that the water flow control knob is too high for her to reach.
It would be great if the flow control is at the handheld side.
At over one hundred and fifty dollars, this can be considered a high end product.
Thats the only negative point I would say.
Other than that, this is a great set.

This light uses a AA battery and the alkaline lasts way longer than my rechargeables li ions I have!!

WOULD I BUY THIS AGAIN?> Yes.

CONS:> The switch to switch between Fahrenheit and Celsius is underneath the battery, so you have to plug the battery in, then hold down the tiny button for a few seconds, and then you can put the battery in and close the lid.> The battery compartment lid has no access hole for your finger tip, so trying to remove it requires you to smack the unit against your hand to jostle the battery door free.

I paid 33 bucks.======================INSTALLATION======================To make sure it would fix my toilet, I visited the Luxe Bidet website before buying it, clicked on FAQ, and read How far does the bidet extend from the side of the toilet?
, which has a diagram with measurements.
My toilet is oblong, not round.
It fits great.
It was easy to install.
It took me 30 minutes or less.
I did not need the flexible water supply hose (the one with the larger connection on one end), since my toilet was already had a hose connected to the cold water supply.
I was careful NOT to over-tighten any of the connections.
For the t-adapter to the toilet base, I hand tightened only, so it was snug.
For the water supply to the t-adapter, I hand tightened only, so it was snug (my existing hose nut was plastic and ribbed for hand tightening).
For the flexible metal-braided hose to the t-adapter, I hand tightened and then used a wrench to tighten only 1/4 turn.
For the hose to the bidet, I also hand tightened and then used a wrench to tighten only 1/4 turn.
No leaks.
What about the plastic t-adapter?Some folks complained that the plastic t-adapter appeared cheap.
Im accustom to plastic parts in my toilet water tank, and I felt that the t-adapter was thick/sturdy enough.
My existing cold water supply hose is plastic and so is its connection to the toilet.
The male connection on the Luxe Bidet is also plastic (the connection where the flexible metal-braided hose fits to the bidet itself).
I situated my bidet against the back of my toilet, and I made sure that the toilet seat plastic screws were tight (so neither the bidet nor the toilet seat would move from side to side).
Since my toilet is oblong, I dont have a problem with the toilet seat sitting above the toilet after installing the bidet.
The seat angles down from back to front, and the front rests on the toilet.

Although there is a gap between the seat and toilet in the back and in the middle, it is not a problem, since the front of the seat rests on the toilet.======================USING THE DEVICE======================I have my toilet water supply valve opened fully for maximum water flow into my toilet (so it flushes properly), so I have plenty of water pressure for the bidet.
For the bidet water control knob on the bidet itself, I turn the knob 1/4 inch or less to get the right amount of water that I need to clean-off.
So, for my water pressure, I dont have to turn the knob very much.
The diagram on the control has 5 settings: off, and 4 dots between low and high.
I dont go past the first low dot (the dot next to off).
The water spray is wide (not a fine pin spray).
Its like the stream of water that comes from a drinking fountain.
I dont use toilet paper anymore.
Instead, I pat myself dry with a small towel, which I hang on the toilet roll hanger.
Since the bidet water gets me clean, the towel also stays clean.
What about using cold water to wash-off?Its not a problem for me.
Its not like Im taking a shower in it.
Its just a small part of the body that gets hit with cold water.
That brings-up another topic...
Its fast!
Using a bidet is faster than using toilet paper.
Sometimes with toilet paper you can get away with a couple of wipes, but most of the time you cant.
With the bidet, it takes the same amount of water to wash-off each time, then pat dry, and youre done.
Much faster and more consistent than using toilet paper.
And of course you get cleaner... less likely to mess-up your underwear.
Some side benefits... No more stopped-up toilet due to using too much toilet paper; most of the time that was not a problem for me, but now it cant happen.

Less smell--probably because Im not repeatedly exposing soiled toilet paper to the air.======================OTHER INFO======================Originally, I was apprehensive about buying an add-on bidet like this, because I was concerned that it would fail, and cause substantial water damage to my home.
However, none of the reviews on Amazon for any of the Luxe Bidet models mentioned something like this happening.
Based on my experience with the Luxe Bidet, Im not concerned about it.
It appears to be a well-made, quality product.
My main motivation for buying a bidet was to stop buying consumables like toilet paper (to save money).
Based on the price I paid for the bidet, the cost of toilet paper in my area, and the amount of toilet paper I normally use, the bidet should pay for itself in about 2 years.
The small cotton towels I purchased for drying off after using the bidet only cost about 3 bucks for a pack of 9 towels.

Other consumables I also eliminated at the same time were paper napkins (use small cotton towels instead), paper tissue/kleenex (use cotton handkerchiefs instead), and paper towels (use small cotton towels instead).

The small cotton towels I purchased were available in 3 different colors, so it is easy to keep them separate.======================CONCLUSION======================Im very pleased with my purchase, and I wish I had done this years ago.
Its much better than toilet paper: cleaner, faster, cheaper over time, and easier on the environment.

I saw these lights shown on an episode of This Old House recently and they received high praise from the contractor on the show.
It wasnt a paid placement Ad and the manufacturers name wasnt even mentioned so the opinion appeared nonbiased.
Previously Id installed some simple LEDs years ago that at the time made a big difference, but thought it was time to try a dimmable upgrade with the latest technology.
The reviewers here showered praise on this product, so I ordered a run of 4 units, 2 of these 24 inch lights and two of the 12 inch models for my small kitchen.
Installation offers you several options.

In the box is, of course the fixture, a cord that can be plugged into the fixture and then directly into the wall outlet with an on/off switch on the cord, one junction box, one hard connector and one bridge wire connector.
You can gang connect several fixtures end to end with the connectors and then use one plug.
Or you can opt to use the various combination options and junction boxes to have them hard wired.
I wanted the hard wired option to be able to control the run of lights with a dimmer switch, in anticipation of the brightness other reviewers spoke of.
The fixtures mount to the underside of the cabinet with just one screw on each end.
Due to the light weight this is sufficient to hold them securely.
Im an avid renovator, but electrical installation still makes me a little nervous.
I can whole heartedly say that the design of this setup made the process almost as simple as snapping legos together.
I used 12/2 Romex for the run from the final junction box to the dimmer switch.
The dimmer switch used was Lutron CTCL-153P-WH CONTOUR CFL/LED.
To test my connections before making the hardwired connection I attached the wired plug with the on off switch and plugged it into an outlet and voila, bright clean light flooded my countertop.
I unplugged the test connection and and made the hardwire connections through the dimmer switch and the installation was complete.
I cant praise these lights highly enough.
The added lighting changed the whole atmosphere of the kitchen and makes it much more conducive to feeling like a place I want to work when preparing meals.

A few reviewers felt the lights are thicker than necessary, but for me they seem unobtrusive and dont interfere with any countertop appliances including my very tall espresso machine and coffee grinder.
If youre reading this youre evidently looking to improve your kitchen lighting situation.
No matter your skill level, you should have no problem installing these and for me, I couldnt possibly be any more pleased with the results.

I received an attentive reply from them in less than 12 hours.

First, I do not own this saw.
I was in the market for a circular saw, I shopped around and fondled many of them in a local store.
The Mag77 is a bulletproof saw no doubt about it.
My father who is a carpenter uses them as does everyone else on his crew.
I have seem them dropped repeatedly, thrown off roofs.
The main gripe about the mag77 is the foot plate.
This lighter version solves that with a more robust foot plate.
The extra 2lbs weight loss is a noticable difference in weight and makes the saw just light enough to hold out with one arm.
The original saw is just too heavy to hold steady with one arm out.
You have to wonder where they managed to shave off 2 lbs from this saw and i have closely inspected it side by side with its competitors.
The only thing I noticed that I did not like is that the RPM spec listed on the motor nameplate is 5300 RPM whereas all the other worm drives are 4600 RPM.
What does this equate to?
I am not sure.
I am guessing less torque.
This is one specification they do not mention on the box or on this product listing so I felt I should write a review to point it out.
This specification is also conveniently left out of the specifications listing on the Skil website, even though all of the other saws have it listed.
I think the people behind this product know it is not really the same saw as the mag77 only lighter and are trying to hide that fact.

I ended up purchasing the Bosch 1677MD saw which is made by the same company, The bosch and the Skil are nearly identical, but the bosch does have the nice sturdy foot plate (albeit not as nice of angle markings)  I went to the store intent on buying this new lighter skil which does have some better features such as the degree markings on the footplate are more precise and detailed.
Also this saw will cut up to 53 degrees.
More than the bosch or the regular mag77.
But I just could not buy the new Mag77lt knowing it has a 700RPM faster speed.
To me that means they shaved the weight off by doing something with the heart of this saw which is the motor and the gear assembly.
You be the judge if it equates to less cutting power.

Weve had problems with the OttLite Craft Lamp since its arrival.
Assembly was easy, but when we first tried to turn the lamp on, the lighting tubes didnt work.
Fortunately, OttLite customer service was receptive, cordial and all-around wonderful.
A replacement was sent out immediately.
Lighting now works, but the stand developed a strange tilt.
We discovered the stem separates from the base, even though it was correctly assembled according to manufacturer instructions.
There is a sleeve that is screwed into the pole at the factory.
OttLite provides a wrench and bolt with a flat washer and lock washer that screws into that sleeve.
The threads on the sleeve are poorly cut but you wont find that out until you try to pick up the lamp and find that the base is still on the floor.
Poor quality control.
There is no way to fix this problem.
I wondered if ours was a unique situation, and was surprised to see at least five other Amazon reviewers have experienced the same problem with their brand new lamps.
I thought about calling customer service again, but after reading the difficulty others had trying to get resolution, Ill just live with the problem instead.
Although the tilt makes me unhappy, it is still functional.
I do find the lamp awkward to use.
It is hard to position because the lamp does not accommodate all chair types easily, especially if the short magnifier arm is being used.
The magnifying glass is plastic, but does its job well enough.
Once positioned, reading light is satisfactory too, but it only illuminates a small area.
Now that I know my OttLites limitations (separation from base), the lamp will stay in a stationary spot and one that it seems designed for--a desk with a straight back chair.
That being said, it doesnt seem right that so many brand new OttLite lamps should have this problem in the first place.
I like these lamps which strike a balance between performance and affordability.
They turn on instantly.
The color rendering index is good and I like the "slightly less warm but still warm" 3000K color temperature.

This three tool combo kit is hands down the best bang for your buck!The Dremel 3000 is nearly the top of the line rotary tool Dremel makes (only two other models are considered better).
The EZ Twist nose cap wrench is awesome!
No separate wrench needed for changing/tightening bits or tools.
Just unscrew the cap, slide it up to the collet nut and tighten!The 3000 fits my hands quite well (I have large hands).
Well balanced and easy to maneuver.
And unlike several other models of Dremels I have this one is actually quieter, very pleased.
The Multi-Max MM20 is awesome!
With a solid and powerful 2.3AMP motor you can power through most anything.
The best feature of this tool are the accessory wood blades for flush cutting.
This comes in extremely handy when doing any sort of flooring or molding work.
Youd be surprised how often you go for this tool instead of a dovetail, detail, or flexible pull saw.
Save a lot of time and is super accurate!
The addition of a detail/corner sander is quite nice as well.
The variable speed adjuster wheel near the back of the handle clicks in place with each increment so you can dial in the perfect speed for your application.
And since it is located near the back, accidental speed changes are highly unlikely.
Tool changes are dirt simple.
Simply undo the clamping screw with the 5mm allen wrench (included with the kit), change the blade/tool, and reinstall the screw.
But the real prize of this kit is the Dremel Saw-Max.
Be it wood, plastic, metal, tile, or whatever, this baby will eat it up!
Boasting a strong 6AMP motor that spins the blade at 17000RPM, the blade seems almost supersonic as to how well and fast it cuts through everything.
The spring loaded depth gauge works great and is easy to use.
In addition to having 1/8, 1/4, 1/2, and 3/4 markings, it also has 5mm, 10mm, 15mm, and 20mm.

This is extremely helpful from me as I work a lot in metric and most plastics and plywoods that I use come in metric, great foresight on Dremels part!The Saw-Max is a bit on the large side and some people may find it a bit difficult to operate one handed.
For me, its just perfect.
All of the tools have just the right amount of cord, long enough to get it plugged into a wall outlet and to your work piece, but not too long that the cord gets in the way.
So again, hands down this is the best Dremel combo kit out there.
Now please excuse me as I go buy some more accessories and blades for this awesome trio of tools!

When your B&D; Workbench arrives youll need a knife of some sort to open it.
Or at least I did.

The top of the packing box is only taped and will come open easily enough, but I found it to be one of those situations where its such a tight squeeze that its virtually impossible to pull the item out.
So I jimmied open the large stapled side.
Inside youll find the black frame, a sub-box (which contains the two wooden boards that look like composite bamboo), and a bag-o-parts and instructions.
I definitely needed the instructions to put the work bench together, although it wasnt difficult.
There are four huge black plastic spacers that the main board sits on.
You run bolts through recessed holes in the board thru the spacers into the frame below.
Theres a tightening tool to do this.
(Note: I found it easiest to finger tighten as I went along from one bolt/spacer alignment to the next.
)Theres a different arrangement for the floating board.
Two black blocks with 1 peg each and one bolt.
After that, theres nothing much to do but place the 4 orange grabbers.
These, of course, can be place so you can clutch 3 and four sided objects.---The biggest thing with workbenches from my perspective is how sturdy they are.
I tested mine by having my husband and teen daughter sit on the bench at the same time.
Not 550 pounds, but quite a bit of weight.
I didnt see any wobbling.

The bench appears very well made, and at the present price, I think its a good buy.--Folds and unfolds fairly easily.--Like most benches theres no real handhold to carry it.--Has a hook locking mechanism.--If you use the orange grabbers, the thinnest object you can grab is about 1/2-inch.
If you use the the 2 boards as clamps, you can obviously grasp exceedingly thin objects.
Im REALLY happy to have received this bench.
Ive got all sorts of projects that I havent tackled because I didnt have this vital/extremely-useful piece of equipment.
The Moen S43001 is a stunning faucet, but is it worth the price premium?BUILDMoen faucets usually are built to last, with some plastic exceptions.
This is definitely not an exception.
The metal is a good gauge, and the moveable parts are sturdy.
There were some minor defects in the metal (small bumps), which is likely not an issue with the quality of the materials so much as an issue with packaging or rough handling.
Make sure to inspect yours before installing.
STYLEOne of the greatest compliments I can give a fixture is that it is not for everyone.
So many faucets are designed with a style generic enough to make a home easy to sell to any consumer.
This faucet instead has a definite style.
The sharp angles have both an urban and a deco style, and the handle is striking and part of the design.
It makes a statement, and it is a statement that I personally like a lot.
FUNCTIONWater flows nicely, without too much or too little aeration.
The handle is a bit stiff, but that lends itself to the substantial feel and allows it to loosen over time without feeling too loose.
Moving from hot to cold is smooth and intuitive.
My only critique is that, while the design works well with a rotating head, the arc of the faucet is fixed in place.
It is sometimes convenient to spin a faucet out of the way.
INSTALLATIONModern Moen faucets have a very streamlined installation process that minimizes plumbing connections and includes a tool to avoid awkward hand-cramping work.
Having installed a lot of faucets, I thoroughly appreciate how easy they come on and off.
Of note here is that the faucets circular base is smaller than a normal.
That means that if you plan to use a base plate to cover a three-hole sink, youll likely still need to use the circular base plate that comes with the faucet.
On the bright side, this stacked look works perfectly with the design.
SUMMARYThis is one of my favorite faucets.
It has a distinct and impressive design, and is a joy to use.

The build quality and finish of this wedge is great, as you would expect from Estwing.
As to performance, on seasoned wood, this wedge is very impressive, especially when you are delivering a really hard blow.
The protrusions give it the extra leverage it needs to ensure a complete split.
Wood with an uneven grain is a little harder, but this wedge is generally still up to the challenge-- it does just as well as any other I have seen.
Green wood is where this wedge gets into trouble.
The tip angle is not especially acute, which ought to ensure excellent durability, but makes it quite hard to set in springy, wetter wood.
It also has a proclivity to bounce out of a green log when you strike it if you fail to drive it about half-way in.

If you are looking for something for splitting dry wood, this wedge is outstanding, but if you are splitting freshly-bucked logs or using a less forceful technique, you might do better to choose a more acutely angled wedge with a sharper tip.

Edit : Ive since found another flashlight / USB power pack that is similar.
TheRAVPower Lusteris similar, except : no dock, no USB AC plug supplied, less powerful flashlight, doesnt look as nice or as well built.
It has a higher stated capacity but I suspect it also uses a 18650 type LiIon battery.
It is significantly less expensive, however.
I own a number of portable chargers, and this one distinguishes itself in a number of ways.
It looks great, the construction is solid, and functionality well thought out.
Its not perfect, but it is close to it.

The product listing is a bit lacking in specs, so here they are :Capacity : 2600 mAh (3.7V, 9.62 Wh)USB output : 5V 1A (for charging other devices with CL3)USB input : 5V 1A (for charging CL3 through micro USB)USB plug output : 5V 2.1AUSB plug input : 100-240V AC, 50-60Hz, 450mAWhat I like about it :1.
It has a very good flashlight.
In fact, I dont know if this is a rechargeable flashlight that can function as a USB battery pack, or a USB battery pack that has a flashlight built in.
The light is a bit bluish, and it is not waterproof, but it is very bright, and you can adjust the brightness level.2.
Recharging is convenient using the dock - just drop it in.
The unit itself has a groove to make sure it can only be inserted in one direction.
The dock is made of metal (I assume aluminum), is heavy, has a rubberized bottom so that it doesnt slide.
It also has a USB port in front to plug in your phone, MP3 player, or other devices for charging.3.
USB wall adapter included.
Its a beefy 2.1A unit, and works at 100-240V / 50-60 Hz in case you want to bring it along when youre traveling overseas.4.
Dual charging options.

You can recharge the CL3 using either the dock (just drop it in - the pogo pins in the dock will touch the recessed contacts on the CL3) or through the micro USB port, for when you dont have the dock with you.5.
Well thought out design.
If youre worried about the light coming on accidentally, there is a lock function.
Press both buttons for a few seconds, and the unit will lock both buttons.
Repeat to unlock before you can use it as a light or USB battery pack.6.
Attractive, easy to hold, light button positioned conveniently for thumb, and can be located by touch.
The CL3 itself is made of anodized aluminum, weighs about 8 oz (estimate - I cant find a scale to measure it precisely) and feels great in the hand.7.
Included power adapter draws hardly any power when not in use - very little vampire / standby power loss.
I left the unit plugged into a Kill-a-Watt.
Although it reported an idle current of 0.05A (which surprised me), power factor (percentage of time it draws power, expressed as a number between 0 and 1) is 0.03 or lower.
I left it plugged in for 12 hours, and the cumulative counter could not detect any power usage.
The resolution is 0.01 Wh.8.
Pass through charging - can charge devices while itself is being charged.
It is not perfect, though :1.
Capacity is quite small - 2600 mAh.
Realistically it means it can recharge a phone fully only about once.
It can power the flashlight at full brightness for about 2 hours, much longer at 10% brightness.2.
Battery is NOT user replaceable.
I cant even see how to open up this unit without breaking it.
From the shape and capacity, I assume the battery inside is a lithium ion 18650 cell, which costs less than $10.
It would be nice if it is user replaceable, especially since the flashlight itself should last for years (LED bulbs have a lifespan of over 50,000 hours).3.
Light is bluish, and occasionally flickers.
I can detect a flicker if the light has been left on full power for a minute or two.
Ive also seen it flickering at 50% and 10% (but not at 100%) when first turned on, and the charge is only about 50% full.
Not sure if this is a defect with my unit only - Ill contact them to find out.
Another minor complain - the only cosmetic imperfection is when you look at the LED - its not perfectly centered.
It doesnt seem to affect the light output at all, and I only mention it because the unit is otherwise so attractive looking.4.
No indicator for how much charge is left.
There is only one visual indicator - a LED that can show green or red.
It would be nice if it can flash to indicate how much charge is left (for example, 4 flashes = full, 3 flashes = 3/4 full and so on).5.
Not waterproof or shockproof.
Ports and contacts at the base are exposed - no protection.6.
No built-in micro USB cable - need to carry your own around.
Need to push button to power the USB port.
Not sure why - most chargers I have will immediately start charging when I plug my device in.7.
High price.
Not too excessive though - a decent 200+ lumens light will cost at least $40.
But such a light will have user replaceable batteries and is waterproof.
If you think you need of a good flashlight and a USB battery pack quite often, and the price doesnt faze you, this device is a great buy - compact, well built, works well.
There are several variants on this shape of light.
This one seems to be head and shoulders better in implementation.
It uses a Lithium-Ion battery instead of a cheaper NiCad or NiMH type cell.
The battery is non-standard and resembles an early Nokia cell phone cartridge.
If you open the unit to see the battery or circuitry, you void your warranty, per the manufacturer.
The maker suggests that the lamp be placed so that the photocell receives 12 hours of direct sunlight.
This is good advice, as the light goes ON at dusk and stays on all night long.
So even though the tiny high intensity LEDs appear to be a super efficient type, there are four of them lit up all night long.
If a creature crosses its path, the Motion Sensor Light will boost the power to illuminate the area.
Seems the effective greater light can cover a good 300 square feet if the lamp is placed anout 6-7 feet high.
My only concern is the black plastic casing.
It seems the plastic will hold a lot of heat from so much sun exposure.
A white casing would certainly be cooler internally.

Perhaps the maker figured that the extra internal heat will help to dissipate collected, evaporating moisture;  the case is NOT water tight, there is an upside-down U-shaped foam gasket that is designed to keep water from dripping directly upon the importand circuit, sensor, or battery cell.
Best case installation would be under a handy roof eave but with enough exposure to get the required 12 hours of sunlight.
I am installing a couple like that and a couple more fully exposed to the elements, so Ill be seeing how these guys survive the rainy season!
I like that its instantly on to full power unlike CFLs.
The light color is a nice soft warm white.
My only concern is about longevity.
My experience with CFLs is that they dont last nearly as long as advertized.
These being even more expensive youll take even more of a financial hit but only time will tell.
Just got it, now using it, definitely brights.
Im using it in my garage and it brightens up the area.
At 12 watts it is well worth it.

My concern with electric screwdrivers, and my problems with ones Ive owned through the years, has been how weak they can be.
At times, Ive found Im better off just twisting the screw in by hand, rather than listen to the hopeless machine as it struggles to rotate the darn thing.
Not so with this little guy.
From the moment you hold this, you can feel its weight and the power that goes with it.

Its strong and sturdy, easily plugged in to recharge, and fits the needs of someone like me, a light user who pretty much just needs it to fix the occasional cabinet handle or assemble some Swedish furniture.

Silly as it may sound, I have about five of this sort of light scattered about the house.
This is because I am a relatively lazy person and hate going through the hassle of constantly dragging these little reading lights from one location to another.

I must say though, that of all the lights I presently own and use and of all the lights from my distant and not so distant past, that the one being reviewed here is right at the top of being best of the lot.
I am extremely happy with it.
To begin with (and I know we are all different as to our light needs) the brightness and intensity of this light meets my reading needs perfectly... and this is what I use this thing for.
The light is bright enough for my eyes to even read fine print (It works great with my old Kindle), and yet it is not so bright that it is harsh and difficult on they eyes.
Then there is the clip... and what a clip it is.

They say that a snapping turtle will not let loose of its victim until it thunders and I am quite sure that the clip on this thing would out-do all but the most determined and largest turtle in the pond.
This puppy holds onto things and holds tight.
I would say though that if you have difficulties with your grip or have heavy arthritis pain, then the spring in this thing may be too much for you and this should be considered before purchase.
The suction cups give a good firm grip on just about everything including fabric and I have encountered not slippage what so ever.
While the LED (3 watt) is NOT replaceable on this item, it, according to the manufacturer has 30,000 hours on it which could quite well out last me.
It is most certainly economical and uses very little electricity.
I love the long goose neck on this thing as it allows me to adjust the light to just about any position I need.

For me this is important as I normally read with at lest three dogs on my lap and quite often have to scrunch myself into very odd positions as I dare not disturb them and their naps.... not that they are spoiled or anything...... For me having the on and off switch on the cord rather on the base is a blessing as it is much handier in my situation.
Some folks will like this; some will not...
I personally find it perfect.
The lamp is attractive and does not offend my wifes dcor sensibilities all that much... a blessing as far as I am concerned.
All in all I am extremely pleased with this lamp and if I make it through the 30,000 hours I plan to purchase another.

I have over one dozen USB-powered devices (tablets, cell phones, power banks, etc.)
in the house, plus almost equal number of USB power adapters.
Sharing USB power supplies among different USB devices is a process of trial and error, since most manufacturers dont provide accuracte description for input/ouput power specs.
Thats why thisUSB Mini Charger Doctorsounds like an useful tool for me.
The USB Doctor is supposed to display the USB ports output voltage and load currently alternately, so that I can monitor its charging progress and also calculate the output power (voltage * current).
In actual testing, however, it does not work as expected.
With no load connected to the USB Doctor, the red LED display correctly cycles between voltage and current reading every 5 seconds or so.
But when there is a load connected, the display stays stuck in one mode (either voltage or current) and does not toggle.
The only way I can see the other mode is to disconnect the load, wait for the display to switch mode, and then reconnect the load again.
I cant tell if my unit is defective or its behavior is by design, since the unit came with ZERO instructions.
In any case, the unit is going back for a refund.
Aside:I verified the accuracy of voltage and current readings using aDigital Multimeter.
The readings are consistent to within 5%, which is not great but acceptable.
[Update on April 24, 2014]I purchased a second unit just to give this product another chance.
The dispaly on this one correctly toggles between Voltage and Current every 3 seconds.
However, the information for Current is completely wrong!
I have a tablet (Vizio) that draws 1.4A while charging, but the display on this unit says 0.42A.
Another tablet (Nook HD+) draws 2.0A while charging, but this unit says 0.00A.
Wrong information is worse than no information.
The second unit is also going back.
[Update on May 3, 2014]I purchased thePortaPow USB Power Monitorand found it to perform exactly as advertised.
It costs 2-3x the price of this USB Doctor but is a much better product.
See my review on it for details:http://www.

Also, the act of picking music is clumsy especially if much of your music library is in the cloud; I know people think Coverflows are cool but they are not an efficient means to get through a song library of thousands of pieces.

This is my new favorite flashlight.
It comes in a great, sturdy box that I plan to keep and repurpose for something else.
It would make an impressive gift presentation to just about anyone (who doesnt need a good flashlight?).
The flashlight itself is very bright and extremely well-made and sturdy, constructed of high-strength aerospace aluminum alloy.
I believe it.
The instructions claim that its waterproof (probably, but Im not going to test it).

The rim around the lens is scalloped for no apparent reason, so I can only assume that this flashlight is designed to double as a weapon (makes sense; the instruction manual cryptically boasts that this flashlight is anti-wrestling).
If you jab this thing into someone, you could easily do some damage.
This would be handy if you are ever confronted during levee patrol, which the manual recommends this flashlight for.
But dont think that this flashlight is only for commando types; the manual also recommends its use for the appreciation of jewelry.
Okay, the manual needs to be edited by someone who speaks better English, but dont let that stop you from getting this flashlight.
Its GREAT.
All kidding aside, I love this flashlight.
The fact that it can easily be recharged with the included charger is icing on the cake, and since I dont have to worry about running down the batteries, Im going to use it all the time.
My husband (who lost my last flashlight) has already expressed interest in it, but I menaced the serrated rim at him, and he backed off.
In one of the pictures on the Amazon product page, the flashlight is shown sitting in what appears to be a little stand.
My flashlight, alas, did not come with any sort of stand.
It just has the charger (which charges the battery in-place; no need to remove it).
There are three different light settings: low, high, and seizure-inducing strobe.

Ive used the DEWALT 200 PSI Quiet Trim Compressor to install wainscoting in our dining room and just completed changing out some damaged trim in my home office.
The compressor saved me considerable time and effort and performed perfectly with very little kickback.
The next job will be installing crown molding in our living room.
In the meantime, I picked up the TEKTON 5-piece quick coupler ($6.77) and a tire inflator -- so Ill never have to return to the gas station to refill my car tires.
Ive also used it to fill our huge inflatable pool (for our 2 large dogs), my riding lawnmowers tires, as well as the tires of our bicycles and a soccer ball.
Extremely convenient!For the inflatable pool, since it is rather large, I need to let the compressor fill up for a few minutes before using it.
I had been using a small electric air compressor which took 45 minutes to fully inflate the pool.

The compressor is light enough to pickup and move with no problems yet heavy enough not to get dragged about when working with a long hose.

Also, how quiet it is compared to my Firestorm, make it worth the extra money.
I look forward to many years of using this compressor.
The first thing that someone buying the SentrySafe SFW205CWB will say when they receive the safe is that it is heavy and it is large.
The safe weighs in over 138 pounds and it is has dimensions of 19.3 x 18.6 x 23.8 inches.
Thus, for the sake of comparison, it is slightly larger than a mini fridge and weighs about 3.5 times as much.

In fact, when I first opened it and when my children first saw it, we all asked, Is it really a mini-fridge?  Please make plans before you order this of where you are going to put it AND how you are going to get it there.
This is one product that I hope to never have to test its durability when it comes to fire or water.

Since I do not have a way to put this safe through a fire or retrieve it if I submersed in under water, I think it is vital that I share up front the manufacturers warnings that are in the manual about what not to store in this safe.
It states that guns are not to be stored in here.
It states not to store delicate items, such as photos, stamps, and jewelry with working parts, directly in the safe, as the safe will accumulate moisture.
They recommend using airtight containers for storage of these within the safe.
It clearly states not to store pearls in this safe due to their lower tolerance to temperatures.
It also warns to not store computer disks, audio-visual cassettes, or photo negatives.
With those particular warnings, I am not sure what I would directly store in here except for some documents for which this large of a safe would currently be an overkill.
The overall outside body of the safe seems extremely well-built and solid.
However, the lock dial feels extremely cheap, especially when you turn it.
Though I am sure the safe has been rigorously tested, I have some hesitations that the dial will not fail when exposed to high temperatures.
In other words, I did not feel well about the security of the dial.
There is a ton of space inside of this safe, though as I mentioned early, I am not sure if I feel very comfortable in putting much inside of it.
It has a drawer, a shelf, a storage pocket, and side pegs for holding keys and other small hanging objects.
It has six large pins on the edge of the door used for securing the door tightly when locked.
The door does feel very secure when locked, which is a definite positive.
Overall, I just did not have a good feeling about this safe for overall protection of the items that I need to be secured.
Its greatest asset seems to be that it is so heavy that a thief may have second thoughts about trying to walk off with it.
Im not sure if its due to circuitry, a consequence of the tool and battery communicating, or what but its got to be something that can be improved.
I hope Bosch reads these reviews and/or improves the triggers.
Drill and batteries made in Malaysia, charger in China, and L-BOXX in Germany.
I used epoxy to glue it back on and its holding up now.
Actually, it was a cylindrical portion under the latch.
Ill note that the L-BOXX came with a latch broken due to Im guessing rough handling.
All other matters relating to the tool are great though.
I really hate to have to give the tool only four stars, but with the trigger issue I cant give it five in good conscience.
My Makita tools have superior triggers and I can control them so well because of their excellent, sensitive triggers that give great feedback.
The Bosch tools are really impressing me with their quality, features, and innovations, but the triggers need improvement.
This is really strange and not something I like at all.
I tried different batteries, tried contact cleaner on the contacts of the battery and drill, and nothing.
At least one other reviewer has experienced the same thing, as seen in my comments/questions to them.
When changing batteries, the first time the trigger is pulled will not illicit ANY response from the tool for Id say at least 1/3 of a second.
The trigger on this tool has all those, but one very strange issue.
They feel like the travel is long, the response is slow, and generally dont give good feedback.
Some of the other Bosch tools I have, have less than sensitive triggers.
The trigger on this drill is the worst Ive ever experienced.
Now, for the Achilles heel I mentioned in my title.
Regular, non hammer drills have never done this to Ive noticed.
Im guessing it has something to do with the hammer mechanism and/or the fact that the chuck needs to be able to move back and forth.
Ive concluded that this is probably normal with hammer drills because my Makita LXT hammer drill does the same thing.
When the chuck comes to a sudden stop, there is, for me, a noticeable "clank" or "ratcheting" sound.
One thing I want to make sure to note, and I posed this question to two other reviewers, was a "clanking" sound when suddenly letting off the trigger in speed mode 2.
This drill does have less torque than the non brushless motor DDS181 at 442in/lb VS 600in/lb respectively.
The driver setting has 18 clutch settings to dial in the amount of torque needed, but honestly I almost never use these.
You can select between hammer drill, driver, and drill with a rotating sleeve.
The chuck holds tight though, and I didnt experience loosening when drilling into concrete.
If youre drilling a few holes for Tapcons with this then itll work OK, but if you need to drill a bunch of 3/8" or 1/2" holes in masonry then use a rotary hammer.
Being a hammer drill it can be used to drill masonry, but, in my opinion anything bigger than a 1/4" hole is time wasted with a hammer drill, especially a cordless one.
Also, the light on this drill doesnt cast much of a shadow.
The belt clip is great though, cant live without it.
I found the on board bit storage less of an asset on this tool because when its screwed on (to the opposite side of the belt clip) the L-BOXX doesnt close properly.
They charge relatively fast, about 30 minutes.
The digital fuel gauge is great, and frankly a must with Li-Ion batteries.
Even though these are only 2Ah they do last quite a while, especially with the brushless motor.
The drill itself has great balance, especially with the smaller batteries.
Typical fit and finish and quality of Bosch.
This is another great Bosch tool.

com, and check.

The Panasonic FV-CSVK1 WhisperGreen Select-Plug and Play condensation sensor module, made in China, when used with the PanasonicFV-05-11VKL1,FV-11-15VKL1and associated customizable WhisperGreen Select ventilation fan/lights detects condensation levels and turns on when needed.

If youre wanting to customize your Panasonic WhisperGreen Select ventilation fan/light, the condensation sensor module will most likely pay for itself and is worth your consideration.

Im a homeowner and do-it-yourselfer.
I have a few power tools (drill, random orbit sander, saber saw, recip saw), and occasionally need another.
This month we refinished a wood floor and trim, and ended up replacing a number of floor boards.
The UltraSaw was the perfect tool for cutting all the materials, and the ability to do plunge cuts allowed us to do some things that I dont know how we would have done otherwise.
So Im thrilled we had this saw, and Im sure I will reach for it again soon.
But there were two things that drove me crazy: First, theres a dust port, but no attachment for a bag or a vacuum cleaner.
What exactly are you supposed to do with the dust?
When refinishing floors, you think a lot about dust, and there was no good answer here.
Second, the blades work well, but they wear out fast.
This is exactly the same comment I would make about my Dremel Roto-Tool, but tiny blades for the Roto-Tool are cheap.
Blades for the Ultra-Saw are not.
Watch the videos.
This saw excels at all of the tasks shown.
But be prepared to go buy new blades every time.

This Sylvania LED floodlight has a sturdy construction and a slim base that would go into any RB30 fixtures.
It is rated for indoor and outdoor use.
It is instant-on and dimmable.
its 2700K color temperature tends to be as warm as a soft white incandescent bulb.
This light temperature is great if you want to replace your existing incandescent bulbs but without changing the overall warmness of the light in your home.
I have aGE Lighting 69193 Reveal LED 12-Watt (65-watt equivalent) 630-Lumen BR30 Dimmable Indoor Flood Light Bulb with Medium Basethat is slightly cooler (whiter) than this Sylvania floodlight.
On paper, the GE takes 12W to generate 630 lumens while this Sylvania takes only 9W to generate 650 lumens.
The difference amounts to less than a dollar of electricity per year.
Both lights are very similar in features.
Typically LED lights have a consistent light output through their life, unlike their incandescent counterparts which deteriorate in terms of light output over time.
LEDs have a general life expectancy of 50,000 hrs but their driver electronics usually fail before the LEDs do.
Whether this particular Sylvania floodlight would last as long as other floodlights would remain to been seen.
This Sylvania LED floodlight has a 5-year warranty.
There are many LED floodlights of different brands.
They generally have similar features and operating cost of less than $2 per year.
In other words, they have a difference of a dollar of two in the operating cost throughout their life.
LED lights can usually be dimmable and usable indoor and outdoor.
I would let the unit price be the primary determining factor as to which one to get.
At any rate, this Sylvania LED floodlight is a great choice to have.

Other reviewers have thoroughly covered this lantern so I am going to add a few reasons why I not only fell in love with the review sample that I received, but why I am purchasing more.
It took me a few minutes to figure this thing out after I unboxed it, but when I discovered where the switch is cleverly located I was surprised that it turned on before I inserted batteries.
I then discovered that the battery compartment is an extra source of power in the event of a prolonged outage when you can no longer charge it.
That impressed me because I still have vivid memories of being without electricity for over a week when the hurricanes came through my neck of the woods ten years ago.

However, the reason why I am purchasing more is this lantern draws such a negligible amount of current when the USB charger is plugged it and the lights are activated, that it is an economical way to provide ambient light in the evening.
Plus the hanger makes it handy to actually hang these on my patio or even off a curtain rod.
Another feature I love the the ability to control the illumination from bright to dim.
Note, though, that even at the brightest setting this is not exactly a reading light.
It is designed to work upside down as a lantern or rightside up as a table light, so its versatile as well.
Rarely do I instantly fall in love with a product, but in the case of this light I did and have enthusiastically recommended it to friends and family.
That is the highest endorsement that I can give it and the most sincere as well.
This solves one of the problems I had with LED bulbs -- they dont fit into certain lamps that are built for conventional incandescent bulbs.
Unlike other LEDs, the form factor of this one is very similar to an incandescent, making it a perfect fit for my lamp with a clip-on shade.
The build quality feels very solid.
Ive used several other G7 bulbs, and all have been excellent performers (zero failures to date).
This is no exception, with a very solid, durable feel to it.
The light output is excellent.
I used it to replace a 60w incandescent, and the light output is easily the same, if not better.
Considering it only uses 10 watts, its a great way to minimize electric usage while maintaining good light quality and output.
As with LEDs in general there is little heat output -- you can handle the bulb with bare hands even after it has been on for a while.
Im very pleased with this and would certainly recommend it highly if youre looking for an LED replacement that maintains the traditional light bulb size and form factor.
